WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:19.400
Shakespeare's T-Shop, an idea is born.

00:19.400 --> 00:21.160
Pass the sugar, dear.

00:21.160 --> 00:24.080
Yes, dear.

00:24.080 --> 00:26.960
Can I have the sugar, dear?

00:26.960 --> 00:29.480
Yes, dear.

00:29.480 --> 00:31.240
Hell?

00:31.240 --> 00:32.440
Sorry, dear.

00:32.440 --> 00:33.880
Oh, it's all right.

00:33.880 --> 00:35.080
I can do it myself.

00:39.720 --> 00:41.680
What are you doing today, Pete?

00:41.680 --> 00:43.080
Sorry.

00:43.080 --> 00:46.120
I said, what are you doing today?

00:46.120 --> 00:49.160
I'm not sure at the moment, dear.

00:49.160 --> 00:50.080
But don't worry.

00:50.080 --> 00:50.600
I will.

00:50.600 --> 00:52.760
But I do worry, Pete.

00:52.760 --> 00:54.320
You have no job.

00:54.320 --> 00:55.600
We have no money.

00:55.600 --> 00:57.360
What are we going to do?

00:57.360 --> 00:59.200
Something will turn up.

00:59.200 --> 01:00.040
You see?

01:00.040 --> 01:02.000
Nothing will turn up, Pete.

01:02.000 --> 01:04.280
You just sit at home all day.

01:04.280 --> 01:07.280
Well, what do you suggest?

01:07.280 --> 01:11.800
We need to think, see what ideas we can find.

01:11.800 --> 01:13.320
Maybe I can get a job.

01:13.320 --> 01:15.640
You can't do anything, Mom.

01:15.640 --> 01:17.680
I can do lots of things.

01:17.680 --> 01:19.840
Say something to our daughter, Pete.

01:19.840 --> 01:24.560
Well, let's face it, Josie does have a good point.

01:24.560 --> 01:26.760
What can you do?

01:26.760 --> 01:28.720
Thank you for your support.

01:28.720 --> 01:31.400
It's obvious everyone thinks I'm stupid.

01:31.400 --> 01:35.840
But you don't have any qualifications or experience, my dear.

01:35.840 --> 01:38.560
That's because I married you.

01:38.560 --> 01:39.640
I wanted to be.

01:39.640 --> 01:42.600
I told you not to leave school, Nancy.

01:42.600 --> 01:45.320
Your father said he wasn't good enough for you.

01:45.320 --> 01:48.960
We wanted you to go out with Frank from the bank.

01:48.960 --> 01:50.400
Not now, Mom.

01:50.400 --> 01:51.680
Please.

01:51.680 --> 01:53.360
Your Mom is getting worse.

01:53.360 --> 01:56.240
I told you we need to look for an old people's home.

01:56.240 --> 01:58.440
No, I don't want to go into it.

01:58.440 --> 02:02.320
Don't start arguing at the breakfast table.

02:02.320 --> 02:03.480
Be quiet.

02:03.480 --> 02:05.440
This isn't helping.

02:05.440 --> 02:08.160
We're trying to find some way of bringing some money

02:08.160 --> 02:09.520
into the house.

02:09.520 --> 02:11.800
Why not send your mother out, Nancy?

02:11.800 --> 02:14.680
The local supermarket is always looking for old people

02:14.680 --> 02:16.800
to work at night, stacking shelves.

02:16.800 --> 02:18.520
Don't be so stupid, Pete.

02:21.560 --> 02:24.560
Can you feed Boris, Josie?

02:24.560 --> 02:28.000
But, Mom, why do I just do it?

02:28.000 --> 02:30.080
But, Mom, OK.

02:30.080 --> 02:31.440
I can do it.

02:31.440 --> 02:34.080
Nobody does anything in this house.

02:34.080 --> 02:37.520
Can't you say something to Josephine, Pete?

02:37.520 --> 02:38.520
Yes, dear.

02:43.920 --> 02:46.200
Fairy cakes.

02:46.200 --> 02:47.920
Sorry?

02:47.920 --> 02:51.000
Why are you talking about fairy cakes?

02:51.000 --> 02:52.840
You're good at cooking.

02:52.840 --> 02:56.320
Why not make fairy cakes sell them at the church

02:56.320 --> 02:59.480
bazaar or a car boot sale?

02:59.480 --> 03:00.920
No, Mom.

03:00.920 --> 03:04.560
I don't think that's a very good idea.

03:04.560 --> 03:05.440
Not again.

03:05.440 --> 03:07.920
How often do I tell you, Josephine?

03:07.920 --> 03:10.320
Take that rat up to your room now.

03:10.320 --> 03:12.520
But Dad is hungry.

03:12.520 --> 03:14.960
Who as I tell you?

03:14.960 --> 03:15.960
I hate you all.

03:20.440 --> 03:22.160
Wait a minute.

03:22.160 --> 03:25.920
Maybe what you say, Mom, is a good idea.

03:25.920 --> 03:28.720
Um, I know.

03:28.720 --> 03:30.720
What about a tea shop?

03:30.720 --> 03:32.320
Yes!

03:32.320 --> 03:34.960
We could open a tea shop, Mom.

03:34.960 --> 03:37.040
You and I could make the cakes.

03:37.040 --> 03:40.120
Oh, I love making cakes.

03:40.120 --> 03:43.680
My friends at the Bingo Club love my Swiss roll.

03:43.680 --> 03:47.040
That's not a bad idea, Nancy.

03:47.040 --> 03:49.720
One thing you're good at is cooking.

03:49.720 --> 03:51.640
But wait a minute.

03:51.640 --> 03:53.560
Where do we get the money?

03:53.560 --> 03:56.320
It's not cheap opening up a shop.

03:56.320 --> 03:59.760
Maybe we can get a loan from the bank.

03:59.760 --> 04:01.760
Do you think they would give us some money?

04:01.760 --> 04:03.080
Hmm.

04:03.080 --> 04:04.720
Banks always want to loan money.

04:04.720 --> 04:07.960
But first, we need to write a business plan.

04:07.960 --> 04:11.120
We need to look professional and show the bank

04:11.120 --> 04:13.880
we are serious and know what we are doing.

04:13.880 --> 04:16.040
You're good at that sort of thing, Pete.

04:16.040 --> 04:17.160
OK.

04:17.160 --> 04:18.880
I can start on it today.

04:18.880 --> 04:21.880
We need a concept.

04:21.880 --> 04:27.280
We need a detailed list of costs and our expected income.

04:27.280 --> 04:30.080
But where should we have a tea shop?

04:30.080 --> 04:32.080
Considered a competition.

04:32.080 --> 04:35.960
I think it's better if it's in a village nearby.

04:35.960 --> 04:41.040
Perhaps a traditional English tea shop in an old fashioned village.

04:41.040 --> 04:42.880
Yes, Nancy.

04:42.880 --> 04:45.360
Oh, this is so exciting.

04:45.360 --> 04:47.800
I always wanted to have a shop.

04:47.800 --> 04:50.480
Our own tea shop.

04:50.480 --> 04:53.600
Perhaps we can call it Nancy's nibbles.

04:53.600 --> 04:56.200
I don't think that's a very good name.

04:56.200 --> 04:59.600
What about Britain's best?

04:59.600 --> 05:02.520
First, let's find a shop.

05:02.520 --> 05:04.480
Switch on the computer, Pete.

05:04.480 --> 05:08.120
See if we can find an empty shop in the area.

05:08.120 --> 05:10.400
Can you go and get Josie, please, Mum?

05:10.400 --> 05:12.400
She needs to be involved as well.

05:12.400 --> 05:13.640
Of course, Nancy.

05:17.240 --> 05:19.400
We mustn't get carried away.

05:19.400 --> 05:21.960
Are you sure we're doing the right thing, Nancy?

05:21.960 --> 05:23.240
I'm a bit worried.

05:23.240 --> 05:24.920
We don't have much money.

05:24.920 --> 05:27.240
What happens if it's a disaster?

05:27.240 --> 05:29.640
It won't be a disaster.

05:29.640 --> 05:32.200
I feel it in my bones.

05:32.200 --> 05:34.600
But you know what they say in life.

05:34.600 --> 05:35.480
What's that?

05:35.480 --> 05:37.880
No risk, no fun.

05:37.880 --> 05:40.200
I just hope we're doing the right thing.

05:44.120 --> 05:46.800
On the road.

05:47.680 --> 05:51.120
There are loads of empty shops in the Cotswolds.

05:51.120 --> 05:54.880
Look how much information I got at the estate agents.

05:54.880 --> 05:56.480
Oh, like this one.

05:56.480 --> 06:00.000
It's modern and it's in the centre of Stratford.

06:00.000 --> 06:01.600
It looks awesome.

06:01.600 --> 06:03.040
Look at the price.

06:03.040 --> 06:04.880
It's much too expensive.

06:04.880 --> 06:07.040
What about this one?

06:07.040 --> 06:09.680
It's in Upper Snotlbroth.

06:09.680 --> 06:12.720
My friend Pierre lives in Upper Snotlbroth.

06:12.720 --> 06:13.600
Nice man.

06:13.600 --> 06:15.360
He comes from Germany, I think.

06:15.360 --> 06:16.560
I'm not sure.

06:16.560 --> 06:19.040
He doesn't speak much English.

06:19.040 --> 06:20.640
Nice eyes.

06:20.640 --> 06:24.080
He told me he puts garlic on his waltz.

06:24.080 --> 06:26.160
I think that's what he said.

06:26.160 --> 06:29.440
Are you sure he's German, Mum?

06:29.440 --> 06:31.520
Oh, here, look.

06:31.520 --> 06:33.200
Why a piddle.

06:33.200 --> 06:35.680
That village is only down the road.

06:35.680 --> 06:37.280
Look at the picture.

06:37.280 --> 06:38.080
Hmm.

06:38.080 --> 06:40.400
The price is a bit high,

06:40.400 --> 06:42.160
but maybe we can speak to the owner

06:42.160 --> 06:44.000
and get it reduced a bit.

06:44.000 --> 06:46.160
It looks as if it's going to collapse.

06:46.160 --> 06:47.840
It looks interesting.

06:47.840 --> 06:49.840
Shall we go and look at it now?

06:49.840 --> 06:51.200
Good idea.

06:51.200 --> 06:53.600
Go and get the car out of the garage, dear.

06:53.600 --> 06:54.640
All right.

06:54.640 --> 06:57.680
Ooh, this is so exciting.

06:57.680 --> 06:59.920
I want to put on some makeup.

06:59.920 --> 07:02.640
We're not meeting royalty, Mum.

07:03.280 --> 07:04.720
Come on, Josie.

07:04.720 --> 07:06.480
And bring Boris with you.

07:17.040 --> 07:21.040
Ooh, what is wrong with this car?

07:21.040 --> 07:23.040
Piece of junk.

07:23.040 --> 07:25.440
We're going very slowly.

07:25.440 --> 07:27.200
I can walk quicker.

07:27.200 --> 07:29.280
Then why don't you?

07:29.280 --> 07:32.000
What's he saying about me?

07:32.000 --> 07:34.480
He knows I can't hear very well.

07:34.480 --> 07:36.480
Be quiet, both of you.

07:37.520 --> 07:40.960
Now, what could we call a tea shop?

07:41.680 --> 07:44.320
Time for tea, perhaps.

07:44.320 --> 07:47.120
Oh, truly scrumptious.

07:47.120 --> 07:48.160
Yes.

07:48.160 --> 07:49.120
They're OK.

07:51.280 --> 07:53.440
Are you sure this car's all right?

07:53.440 --> 07:54.720
Of course it is.

07:54.720 --> 07:55.920
It's just...

07:55.920 --> 07:57.840
We're going slower and slower.

07:58.800 --> 08:00.080
It's OK.

08:00.880 --> 08:02.640
The car is a bit full today.

08:03.600 --> 08:06.320
Perhaps eating two pieces of toast for breakfast

08:06.320 --> 08:07.440
was a bad idea.

08:08.480 --> 08:10.240
What are you talking about, Nancy?

08:11.200 --> 08:13.600
Oh, ha-ha-ha-ha.

08:13.600 --> 08:14.000
Dad?

08:14.800 --> 08:15.600
Yes, Josie.

08:16.400 --> 08:18.800
I hope you don't mind me mentioning it, but...

08:18.800 --> 08:19.760
Yes, yes.

08:19.760 --> 08:20.560
What is it?

08:20.560 --> 08:23.760
Well, our next door neighbour has just overtaken us.

08:23.760 --> 08:24.560
So?

08:24.560 --> 08:25.680
He was on his bike.

08:27.280 --> 08:28.640
Yes, that's right.

08:28.640 --> 08:29.120
Laugh.

08:29.120 --> 08:30.000
I don't mind.

08:32.000 --> 08:34.080
Oh, no, look.

08:34.080 --> 08:35.280
What is it, Mum?

08:35.280 --> 08:36.400
What's the matter?

08:36.400 --> 08:38.960
A hill in front of us.

08:39.040 --> 08:40.400
What happens now?

08:40.400 --> 08:41.040
Help!

08:41.040 --> 08:41.840
A hill!

08:45.840 --> 08:50.000
Oh, we need a theme for the shop.

08:50.000 --> 08:50.880
Good idea.

08:51.600 --> 08:53.920
Something that's a bit different.

08:53.920 --> 08:57.040
We can all put on fancy dress clothes.

08:57.040 --> 08:58.000
No, Mum.

08:58.000 --> 08:59.520
Yes, of course.

09:00.400 --> 09:01.120
Why not?

09:02.080 --> 09:06.000
Everyone can dress up in Elizabethan costumes.

09:06.000 --> 09:08.320
You're not serious, are you, Josie?

09:09.280 --> 09:11.920
Why Elizabethan costumes?

09:11.920 --> 09:13.840
It's obvious, Mum.

09:13.840 --> 09:15.760
I want to be lady-dyed.

09:17.040 --> 09:18.560
She was so beautiful.

09:19.120 --> 09:20.080
What a pity!

09:20.080 --> 09:23.680
I think your grandmother's a bit confused with her history.

09:24.480 --> 09:25.760
No, Mum.

09:25.760 --> 09:29.040
Elizabethan is the time of Elizabeth the first.

09:29.040 --> 09:31.520
I'm not talking about Elizabeth the second.

09:32.320 --> 09:34.320
Elizabeth the first was in 17...

09:35.920 --> 09:36.560
16?

09:37.520 --> 09:39.440
Well, a long time ago.

09:40.400 --> 09:42.720
But anyway, I don't understand.

09:42.720 --> 09:44.560
Why Elizabethan, Josie?

09:45.200 --> 09:48.320
Well, my piddle is very near Stratford.

09:49.040 --> 09:49.440
So?

09:50.240 --> 09:51.120
Oh, Mum.

09:52.960 --> 09:54.400
Did you ever go to school?

09:55.520 --> 09:58.880
Shakespeare, William Shakespeare, was born there.

09:59.920 --> 10:02.400
Oh, yes, of course.

10:02.960 --> 10:03.520
Yes.

10:04.480 --> 10:07.680
We can call the tea shop the Shakespeare tea shop.

10:08.240 --> 10:12.960
Oh, no, better is the only Shakespeare tea shop.

10:13.760 --> 10:16.240
It sounds older and more traditional.

10:16.240 --> 10:19.760
We can then dress up in clothes from Shakespeare's time

10:19.760 --> 10:21.360
and attract tourists.

10:23.520 --> 10:26.480
Dad, can dress up in a pair of tights in the shop

10:26.480 --> 10:28.160
to look like William Shakespeare.

10:29.520 --> 10:30.720
What did you say?

10:30.720 --> 10:32.480
Oh, don't worry, Pete.

10:32.480 --> 10:34.880
Josephine didn't say anything important.

10:42.080 --> 10:43.680
Looking at the tea shop.

10:45.040 --> 10:46.720
It's very quiet here.

10:47.680 --> 10:49.360
Is anyone alive here?

10:50.640 --> 10:52.560
It's a lovely village.

10:53.280 --> 10:55.760
Lots of wonderful old buildings.

10:56.480 --> 10:58.560
Oh, there's the village pub.

10:58.560 --> 11:01.520
And look, an old church.

11:01.600 --> 11:03.440
It's really nice here.

11:03.440 --> 11:05.120
It's so peaceful.

11:06.000 --> 11:08.960
There's more life in a funeral procession.

11:08.960 --> 11:10.560
Look, there it is.

11:11.120 --> 11:12.480
Isn't it cute?

11:13.280 --> 11:14.000
Is that it?

11:14.800 --> 11:16.160
Next to the village shop.

11:17.120 --> 11:18.480
God, it's awful.

11:19.360 --> 11:21.200
Oh, it's lovely.

11:21.200 --> 11:22.800
Lots of wooden beams.

11:23.440 --> 11:25.920
It needs a lot of work doing on it.

11:25.920 --> 11:27.520
We have to lower the price.

11:27.520 --> 11:30.240
The bank won't give us enough money for this place.

11:30.240 --> 11:32.160
Don't be so negative, Pete.

11:32.880 --> 11:35.280
We can ask in the village shop next door.

11:35.280 --> 11:36.720
Perhaps they know the owner.

11:37.280 --> 11:37.760
Come on.

11:46.400 --> 11:47.760
Good morning.

11:47.760 --> 11:49.920
I wonder if you can help us.

11:49.920 --> 11:51.280
I certainly hope I can.

11:51.920 --> 11:54.240
What an enchanting blouse.

11:54.240 --> 11:55.040
It looks new.

11:55.680 --> 11:56.560
Silk, isn't it?

11:57.200 --> 11:58.720
Yes, it is.

11:58.720 --> 11:59.920
And thank you.

12:00.960 --> 12:02.960
My name is Nancy Britton,

12:02.960 --> 12:04.800
and this is my husband, Pete.

12:06.080 --> 12:08.880
And a lovely little doggy woggy.

12:09.920 --> 12:11.200
Doggy woggy.

12:12.160 --> 12:13.600
What a doggy woggy.

12:13.600 --> 12:17.920
And this is my daughter, Josephine, and my mother.

12:18.720 --> 12:21.280
It's so enchanting to meet you all.

12:21.280 --> 12:22.720
What can I do for you?

12:22.720 --> 12:27.120
Well, my husband and I are interested in the shop next door.

12:27.200 --> 12:29.440
We're thinking of opening a tea shop.

12:29.440 --> 12:32.800
How enchanting new neighbours.

12:32.800 --> 12:33.440
Come on.

12:33.440 --> 12:34.640
I have a key.

12:34.640 --> 12:36.800
Oh, how terrible of me.

12:36.800 --> 12:38.960
I didn't introduce myself.

12:38.960 --> 12:40.320
I'm Simon.

12:40.320 --> 12:41.360
Call me Si.

12:41.360 --> 12:42.080
Everyone does.

12:42.720 --> 12:43.600
Julian, dear.

12:43.600 --> 12:44.960
Look after the shop.

12:44.960 --> 12:46.720
Back in two shakes of a lamb's tail.

12:47.360 --> 12:47.920
Come on.

12:47.920 --> 12:48.800
Come on.

12:48.800 --> 12:49.760
We can look together.

12:57.120 --> 13:04.560
What a wonderful shop.

13:04.560 --> 13:06.240
It's perfect.

13:06.240 --> 13:09.200
God, who lived here Henry VIII?

13:10.080 --> 13:12.400
Does it have electricity and running water?

13:13.280 --> 13:14.720
Of course it does.

13:14.720 --> 13:16.480
It's too expensive.

13:16.480 --> 13:17.440
I need the loo.

13:17.440 --> 13:18.640
Oh, wait for me.

13:18.640 --> 13:19.520
I do too.

13:20.880 --> 13:23.280
There's a lot of work to do.

13:23.280 --> 13:25.120
It looks rather run down.

13:25.760 --> 13:26.720
Hmm.

13:26.720 --> 13:28.240
It's very old-fashioned.

13:28.800 --> 13:30.240
Even older than your mother.

13:30.240 --> 13:31.200
If that's possible.

13:32.160 --> 13:33.440
You're so funny.

13:34.080 --> 13:35.840
I wasn't trying to be funny.

13:35.840 --> 13:36.400
Oh, I see.

13:37.360 --> 13:39.520
I can see we're going to have such fun together.

13:40.320 --> 13:40.720
Yes.

13:42.000 --> 13:43.360
Is there a kitchen?

13:43.360 --> 13:43.920
Of course.

13:44.560 --> 13:47.360
Julian and I always kept it spotless.

13:47.360 --> 13:49.280
We're real little housewives together.

13:50.000 --> 13:51.280
I don't understand.

13:51.840 --> 13:52.640
Oh no, of course.

13:53.120 --> 13:54.720
Julian and I own this shop.

13:55.200 --> 13:58.320
We moved our village shop next door because it's bigger.

13:58.320 --> 14:00.080
So now we want to rent this shop.

14:01.120 --> 14:02.880
The toilet's in the garden.

14:03.680 --> 14:05.520
It's an outside lav.

14:05.520 --> 14:07.200
Oh, it's like the middle ages.

14:07.200 --> 14:08.960
It's so wonderful.

14:09.680 --> 14:11.520
Reminds you of your childhood, does it?

14:12.240 --> 14:13.440
There you go again.

14:13.440 --> 14:15.200
Your husband's so funny.

14:15.200 --> 14:17.440
We're going to get on like a house on fire.

14:18.640 --> 14:20.080
I'm going back to my shop.

14:21.280 --> 14:23.280
Bring the key when you finish looking round.

14:23.280 --> 14:23.680
Bye.

14:25.920 --> 14:29.040
Well, what do you think?

14:29.040 --> 14:31.280
I'm very happy I'm married to you.

14:31.280 --> 14:32.960
Oh, I mean the shop.

14:32.960 --> 14:33.920
What do you think?

14:34.880 --> 14:36.400
It's a lot of work.

14:36.400 --> 14:37.520
I'm a bit worried.

14:37.520 --> 14:39.440
It's wonderful.

14:39.440 --> 14:42.800
We must all help and that includes you, Josie.

14:42.800 --> 14:43.840
Of course, Mom.

14:44.400 --> 14:46.160
Have you told Dad about the toys?

14:47.040 --> 14:47.840
Sorry.

14:47.840 --> 14:49.120
What did you say?

14:49.120 --> 14:49.920
Tights.

14:49.920 --> 14:50.640
Don't worry.

14:50.640 --> 14:51.520
You don't have to.

14:52.320 --> 14:54.000
Don't have to what?

14:54.000 --> 14:54.720
Come on then.

14:55.120 --> 14:57.200
Let's take the key back to Julian and Cy.

14:58.240 --> 14:59.840
I want to have a word with them.

14:59.840 --> 15:01.440
It's much too expensive.

15:01.440 --> 15:03.120
There's so much to renovate.

15:04.560 --> 15:05.600
What's this about?

15:05.600 --> 15:06.560
Tights, Josie?

15:07.120 --> 15:09.280
Don't tell Julian and Cy.

15:09.280 --> 15:10.400
They'll get excited.

15:14.560 --> 15:16.720
What are you all talking about?

15:20.000 --> 15:21.360
Oh, hello again.

15:21.360 --> 15:23.120
Well, what do you think?

15:23.120 --> 15:24.880
We really like it.

15:24.880 --> 15:26.880
It's just what we're looking for.

15:26.880 --> 15:30.080
Ah, I think it's a bit expensive

15:30.080 --> 15:33.520
and then there's the deposit as well.

15:33.520 --> 15:35.600
And it needs a lot of renovation.

15:35.600 --> 15:36.960
We'll have to do it ourselves.

15:36.960 --> 15:38.320
I know, I know.

15:39.280 --> 15:43.200
Why don't we all meet next week at the estate agent's office?

15:43.200 --> 15:46.240
We can then discuss the money and the contract together.

15:46.240 --> 15:47.600
I'm sure we can agree.

15:47.600 --> 15:48.640
What do you think?

15:48.640 --> 15:50.480
Yes, that's a good idea.

15:51.280 --> 15:54.000
Here's our name and phone number.

15:54.000 --> 15:56.160
Just ring us up to tell us when the meeting is.

15:56.880 --> 15:58.000
Wonderful.

15:58.000 --> 15:59.040
Thank you so much.

15:59.600 --> 16:00.560
Come on, everyone.

16:01.120 --> 16:04.000
Let's go and look around the village and meet the locals.

16:04.000 --> 16:05.680
Not so fast, dear.

16:05.680 --> 16:07.120
One step at a time.

16:07.120 --> 16:09.440
A lot of things can go wrong, you know.

16:09.440 --> 16:11.840
Don't talk such rubbish, Pete.

16:11.840 --> 16:12.960
Come on, everyone.

16:16.160 --> 16:17.360
Women, I know what you mean.

16:21.440 --> 16:22.800
Setting up the tea shop.

16:23.840 --> 16:26.640
Don't let your father see that you have Robbie with you.

16:26.640 --> 16:28.240
You know he hates it.

16:28.240 --> 16:29.920
I want him to see the tea shop.

16:30.560 --> 16:32.800
You want to see a doney Robbie.

16:32.800 --> 16:34.800
Just a bit hidden, please, Josie.

16:35.520 --> 16:37.120
You need to put it on a diet.

16:37.840 --> 16:38.960
But he's not fat.

16:39.760 --> 16:41.920
Come here, little Robbie, I still love you.

16:42.880 --> 16:46.720
I love the old tables and chairs you found Nancy.

16:46.720 --> 16:49.760
Yes, eBay is a wonderful thing.

16:49.760 --> 16:50.880
B-day?

16:50.880 --> 16:52.720
Have we got one of those as well?

16:52.720 --> 16:53.920
Sorry, mother.

16:53.920 --> 16:56.880
My friend Pierre in Upper Snottlebrough

16:56.880 --> 16:58.560
has one in his bathroom.

16:58.560 --> 16:59.680
I saw it.

16:59.680 --> 17:01.280
He washes his socks in it.

17:02.160 --> 17:03.600
I think that's what he said.

17:03.600 --> 17:04.560
I'm not sure.

17:04.560 --> 17:06.080
I don't speak German.

17:06.080 --> 17:06.800
No, mum.

17:06.800 --> 17:07.760
I said...

17:07.760 --> 17:08.880
Oh, it doesn't matter.

17:09.920 --> 17:11.520
Are you sure he's German, mum?

17:12.160 --> 17:14.080
If his name's Pierre, then he's...

17:14.080 --> 17:15.440
I think so.

17:15.440 --> 17:16.480
He looks German.

17:17.360 --> 17:18.720
What does it German?

17:20.480 --> 17:21.600
What's that noise?

17:22.960 --> 17:23.760
Oh, yes.

17:24.320 --> 17:26.480
It's the shop sign company.

17:26.480 --> 17:28.720
They're putting up the sign on the front of the shop.

17:29.280 --> 17:31.040
It's so exciting.

17:31.040 --> 17:32.960
Our own t-shop.

17:32.960 --> 17:34.160
One, two.

17:34.160 --> 17:34.640
Coming.

17:35.920 --> 17:38.640
Mum, can you and Josie start to think about

17:38.640 --> 17:40.640
what to write on the menus?

17:40.640 --> 17:43.600
Oh, and can you keep an eye on the men outside?

17:44.160 --> 17:47.680
Check they don't put the shop sign upside down.

17:47.680 --> 17:48.800
Of course.

17:48.800 --> 17:49.760
Leave it to us.

17:50.720 --> 17:53.920
If this shop's going to have a Shakespeare theme,

17:53.920 --> 17:57.360
then I suppose the food should have a Shakespeare name too.

17:57.360 --> 17:59.760
That's a good idea, Josie.

17:59.760 --> 18:01.440
What do you suggest?

18:01.440 --> 18:02.960
What about, um...

18:03.520 --> 18:05.840
Yorick Yorkshire jam cake?

18:06.800 --> 18:07.520
Or, uh...

18:08.320 --> 18:10.080
Macbeth Marang Pie.

18:11.200 --> 18:12.080
That's good.

18:13.280 --> 18:16.080
How about Stephen Scones?

18:16.960 --> 18:17.840
Sorry, Grant.

18:18.880 --> 18:20.000
I don't understand.

18:20.400 --> 18:22.000
Why Stephen Scones?

18:22.000 --> 18:24.320
He's a good friend at the Bingo Club.

18:24.800 --> 18:28.000
Yes, but there has to be a connection with Shakespeare.

18:28.000 --> 18:29.440
Well, yes, there is.

18:30.000 --> 18:34.640
Stephen took me in his car to the Globe Theatre in London.

18:34.640 --> 18:36.480
It's where Shakespeare performed.

18:36.480 --> 18:39.920
Yes, I know what it is, but no one here knows about Stephen.

18:42.080 --> 18:43.280
What do you want, Pete?

18:44.240 --> 18:46.640
Do you think we're making the right decision?

18:46.640 --> 18:48.720
Oh, not now, Pete.

18:49.280 --> 18:51.360
We both signed the contract.

18:51.360 --> 18:53.520
The opening party is on Saturday,

18:53.520 --> 18:55.920
and there's so much to do, and now...

18:55.920 --> 18:57.760
I'm worried about the money.

18:58.400 --> 19:01.200
I just hope we get enough customers to pay the rent.

19:01.760 --> 19:04.480
And the deposit was bigger than I thought it was going to be.

19:04.480 --> 19:05.840
Stop it, Pete.

19:05.840 --> 19:07.200
Don't go on so.

19:07.200 --> 19:09.520
Did you see the interest we have to pay the bank?

19:10.160 --> 19:12.720
Now I know where the bank manager drives a Mercedes.

19:13.680 --> 19:15.840
And all the money we spent on renovation.

19:15.840 --> 19:17.520
Yes, yes.

19:17.520 --> 19:19.840
Anyway, what did you call me for?

19:21.120 --> 19:22.640
Is this where you want the shelves?

19:23.440 --> 19:24.800
Yes, that's fine.

19:29.200 --> 19:29.680
Oh!

19:31.120 --> 19:31.840
What happened?

19:32.400 --> 19:34.400
Pete, are you all right?

19:34.400 --> 19:37.280
Yes, but these walls are not very thick.

19:37.280 --> 19:38.240
Oh, hello.

19:38.240 --> 19:39.440
What a shock.

19:39.440 --> 19:42.240
Well, Julian, a hole in our lovely wall.

19:42.960 --> 19:44.080
Hello, Simon.

19:44.080 --> 19:45.680
I mean, Si.

19:45.680 --> 19:46.960
I'm sorry, but...

19:46.960 --> 19:49.040
Her heart stopped for a second,

19:49.040 --> 19:51.120
trying to spy on us, were you?

19:52.640 --> 19:54.400
No, of course not.

19:54.400 --> 19:56.080
I'm sorry about the wall.

19:56.080 --> 19:57.520
I can repair it.

19:57.520 --> 19:58.160
That's OK.

19:58.160 --> 19:59.520
It's rather fun.

19:59.520 --> 20:00.800
We can talk to each other.

20:01.520 --> 20:04.960
Pete, you're making more work for us.

20:04.960 --> 20:06.960
We open on Saturday,

20:06.960 --> 20:08.880
and we still have so much to do.

20:09.520 --> 20:11.120
I want to do some painting.

20:11.840 --> 20:12.880
Yes, dear.

20:12.880 --> 20:15.200
Can you get me the ladder and the paint, please?

20:15.200 --> 20:16.160
They're in the kitchen.

20:16.720 --> 20:17.680
Yes, dear.

20:23.120 --> 20:24.320
Where do you want me to put...

20:24.320 --> 20:25.840
A be careful, Boris is like...

20:29.600 --> 20:31.120
Oh, my God!

20:31.920 --> 20:33.120
Look at Boris!

20:33.760 --> 20:35.600
He's covered in paint,

20:35.600 --> 20:36.880
and the floor...

20:36.880 --> 20:37.920
Look at the floor!

20:38.480 --> 20:40.320
How stupid you are!

20:41.280 --> 20:42.640
I'm going outside,

20:42.640 --> 20:45.120
and you can clean everything up before I get back.

20:47.280 --> 20:48.000
Yes, dear.

20:49.280 --> 20:50.320
Pete?

20:50.320 --> 20:50.960
Come here.

20:51.920 --> 20:53.440
Where are the workmen?

20:53.440 --> 20:54.560
Gone home already?

20:55.440 --> 20:57.440
Yes, dear. Is there a problem?

20:57.440 --> 21:00.560
Why did I let you organise the sign?

21:01.200 --> 21:03.440
Now I know why they were so cheap.

21:03.440 --> 21:05.280
We need to save money.

21:06.000 --> 21:07.440
It looks very nice to...

21:08.240 --> 21:09.920
Ah, me.

21:11.120 --> 21:14.400
Mum, Josephine, come here.

21:16.320 --> 21:18.800
Why didn't you keep an eye on them?

21:18.800 --> 21:20.480
We can't do everything.

21:20.480 --> 21:22.160
I like the colours,

21:22.160 --> 21:23.840
so bright and cheerful.

21:24.720 --> 21:27.760
I don't think mum is angry about the colours, Gran.

21:27.760 --> 21:28.800
What's the problem?

21:29.680 --> 21:32.000
Oh, I see now.

21:32.000 --> 21:32.800
Silly me.

21:34.400 --> 21:35.920
It's the spelling.

21:35.920 --> 21:37.680
It's not funny, mum.

21:38.560 --> 21:39.760
Phone them now, Pete.

21:39.760 --> 21:40.960
This moment.

21:40.960 --> 21:41.920
Here's my mobile.

21:42.560 --> 21:44.800
Yes, perhaps I will.

21:45.360 --> 21:47.200
I'm sure there's a good reason.

21:47.200 --> 21:47.920
Yes!

21:47.920 --> 21:50.560
Stupidity is the only possible reason.

21:51.600 --> 21:52.640
I want it changed.

21:59.520 --> 22:00.640
Pete, Britain speaking.

22:01.600 --> 22:03.680
The old Shakespeare tea shop.

22:03.680 --> 22:04.320
Why a piddle?

22:06.160 --> 22:07.440
No, I don't like it.

22:08.640 --> 22:09.120
Why not?

22:10.000 --> 22:10.720
Why not?

22:11.280 --> 22:12.880
I want to tell you why not.

22:14.640 --> 22:16.160
No, the colours are fine.

22:18.000 --> 22:19.680
Yes, it's in the right place.

22:20.560 --> 22:20.880
Yes.

22:22.000 --> 22:23.520
And it's big enough.

22:23.520 --> 22:24.560
The problem is...

22:25.200 --> 22:26.000
the words.

22:27.680 --> 22:29.120
Correct me if I'm wrong,

22:29.120 --> 22:32.160
but I think there is a letter P in the word

22:32.160 --> 22:33.120
Shakespeare.

22:34.080 --> 22:36.000
What do you mean, am I sure?

22:36.000 --> 22:37.040
Of course I'm sure.

22:38.400 --> 22:38.960
What?

22:39.920 --> 22:42.240
You hoped I wouldn't notice.

22:43.200 --> 22:45.040
Of course I noticed.

22:45.040 --> 22:47.200
Anyone with any intelligence can see

22:47.200 --> 22:49.200
that Shakespeare has P.

22:49.200 --> 22:49.680
P.

22:49.680 --> 22:50.240
P.

22:50.240 --> 22:50.720
P.

22:50.720 --> 22:50.880
In the middle.

22:52.320 --> 22:54.320
We can't have the name

22:54.320 --> 22:57.280
the old Shakespeare tea shop, can we?

22:58.720 --> 23:00.720
No one understands that.

23:01.600 --> 23:03.040
What do you say?

23:03.040 --> 23:05.040
I don't believe it.

23:05.040 --> 23:06.240
What's the reason?

23:06.240 --> 23:08.080
He says he didn't have enough

23:08.080 --> 23:10.480
letter P's to put on the sign.

23:10.480 --> 23:11.840
What are you talking about?

23:11.840 --> 23:13.280
Give the phone to me.

23:13.280 --> 23:16.080
This is Mrs. Britain speaking.

23:16.080 --> 23:17.120
Sorry?

23:18.080 --> 23:20.720
I don't want to hear any more excuses.

23:20.720 --> 23:22.880
I want to have a P on our sign

23:22.880 --> 23:24.880
by the end of the afternoon.

23:24.880 --> 23:25.920
Goodbye.

23:25.920 --> 23:28.320
Do you know what I want to hear?

23:28.320 --> 23:30.080
Goodbye.

23:30.080 --> 23:32.080
Do you know what you just said, mum?

23:32.080 --> 23:32.880
Sorry?

23:32.880 --> 23:36.000
This is not the best moment to start laughing, Josephine.

23:37.520 --> 23:38.560
Stop it.

23:38.560 --> 23:39.920
Stop it, Josie.

23:39.920 --> 23:42.160
Oh, what's so funny?

23:42.160 --> 23:44.160
I don't understand.

23:44.160 --> 23:47.520
Mum said she wanted to have a P on our sign.

23:48.960 --> 23:50.960
You are all completely mad.

23:51.600 --> 23:53.120
I'm going inside.

23:58.960 --> 24:00.560
The housewarming party.

24:02.720 --> 24:05.040
Is everything ready for the big opening?

24:05.040 --> 24:06.320
Yes, Nancy.

24:06.320 --> 24:07.280
Don't worry.

24:07.280 --> 24:08.960
I do worry.

24:08.960 --> 24:11.200
I'm sure there's something we've forgotten.

24:11.200 --> 24:12.720
Stay cool, mum.

24:12.720 --> 24:14.240
Everything's OK.

24:14.240 --> 24:16.480
Did you deliver all the invitations?

24:16.480 --> 24:19.200
Josie and I did it last week, Nancy.

24:19.760 --> 24:20.880
The local paper.

24:20.880 --> 24:21.920
I forgot to phone them.

24:21.920 --> 24:23.360
I did it, mum.

24:23.920 --> 24:25.120
They'll be here in a minute.

24:26.000 --> 24:27.760
Everything looks all right in the shop.

24:28.400 --> 24:30.880
Oh, god, it's almost 10 o'clock.

24:30.880 --> 24:33.120
I love the dress is, Nancy.

24:33.120 --> 24:34.880
I feel like a queen.

24:34.880 --> 24:36.480
You look great, too, Dad.

24:37.440 --> 24:40.480
I can't be a waiter in the shop wearing these.

24:40.480 --> 24:42.080
What are the customers going to say?

24:42.640 --> 24:44.000
Come on, Pete.

24:44.000 --> 24:45.680
No one will notice.

24:45.680 --> 24:47.360
No one will notice.

24:47.360 --> 24:49.360
Of course, people will notice.

24:49.360 --> 24:51.760
Everyone will see I'm wearing black tights.

24:52.560 --> 24:53.840
It's too embarrassing.

24:54.640 --> 24:58.160
They are very tights in some places.

24:59.120 --> 25:00.560
And this high colour.

25:00.560 --> 25:01.760
I can't look down.

25:01.760 --> 25:03.440
I can't see what I'm carrying.

25:04.560 --> 25:06.080
Just leave them on.

25:06.080 --> 25:08.400
You look, um, lovely.

25:10.320 --> 25:12.240
Oh, no music.

25:12.240 --> 25:13.280
Sorry, Nancy.

25:13.280 --> 25:14.880
We need some background music.

25:14.880 --> 25:16.400
Oh, that's all right.

25:16.400 --> 25:19.360
I can sing some songs from the Bingo Club.

25:19.920 --> 25:22.720
Old MacDonald had a fight.

25:22.720 --> 25:24.240
Oh, these don't.

25:24.240 --> 25:26.320
We don't want complaints from the neighbours.

25:26.960 --> 25:28.320
No, thank you, Mum.

25:28.320 --> 25:29.600
It's not necessary.

25:31.600 --> 25:32.640
Hello.

25:32.640 --> 25:34.080
Surprise, surprise.

25:34.080 --> 25:36.240
Hello, Si, but what?

25:36.960 --> 25:40.320
These are the Wire Piddle Morrismen.

25:45.200 --> 25:46.880
Julian and I are in the village,

25:46.880 --> 25:48.080
dance group.

25:48.080 --> 25:50.640
Thought it would be nice to dance outside the tea shop

25:50.640 --> 25:52.160
when all the guests arrive.

25:52.160 --> 25:53.840
Oh, how exciting.

25:53.840 --> 25:56.480
Oh, what a super idea.

25:56.480 --> 25:57.680
Thank you, Si.

25:58.800 --> 26:00.640
Oh, thank you, Nancy.

26:00.640 --> 26:01.680
Come on, then.

26:01.680 --> 26:02.880
Outside.

26:02.880 --> 26:04.240
And let's start dancing.

26:07.040 --> 26:08.480
What a cool idea.

26:12.480 --> 26:13.600
First guests are here.

26:13.600 --> 26:14.560
Come on, everyone.

26:15.440 --> 26:17.520
This place is tremendous, congratulations.

26:17.520 --> 26:19.360
How would you love tea to see?

26:19.360 --> 26:21.280
Thank you very much.

26:21.280 --> 26:24.240
Please help yourselves to sandwiches and cakes.

26:24.240 --> 26:26.720
My husband's over there if you'd like a cup of tea.

26:27.680 --> 26:28.560
Yes, that's right.

26:28.560 --> 26:29.360
The one in the tight.

26:31.360 --> 26:33.280
Yes, yes, certainly, madam.

26:33.280 --> 26:35.280
If you could just wait a minute.

26:35.280 --> 26:35.600
Sorry.

26:36.480 --> 26:38.640
I thought you said Darjeeling, sir.

26:39.760 --> 26:41.200
No, I'd see.

26:41.200 --> 26:43.120
You wanted a sand.

26:43.120 --> 26:43.760
Yes?

26:43.840 --> 26:45.360
Yes, I'm doing my best.

26:45.360 --> 26:47.040
Don't get your knickers in a twist.

26:47.760 --> 26:49.600
No, I didn't say anything, sir.

26:50.160 --> 26:52.400
Just contemplating the suicide.

26:53.840 --> 26:56.400
Is there, perhaps, anyone who could help me?

26:56.400 --> 26:58.000
Nancy, Josie?

27:00.640 --> 27:01.280
Thought not.

27:02.000 --> 27:02.240
What?

27:03.040 --> 27:03.520
What?

27:03.520 --> 27:05.360
Yes, of course it's tea.

27:05.360 --> 27:07.440
This is a tea shop, madam.

27:09.680 --> 27:10.400
Good morning.

27:10.400 --> 27:12.560
My name's Michael Trumpleton from the Stratford.

27:12.560 --> 27:14.240
Yes, my name's Pete Britton.

27:14.240 --> 27:17.360
And that over there is my lovely, domineering wife.

27:17.360 --> 27:19.760
And the laughing hyena is her mother.

27:19.760 --> 27:21.040
Can't you see I'm busy?

27:21.040 --> 27:22.240
You don't understand.

27:22.240 --> 27:24.000
I'm, can you wait your turn, please?

27:24.000 --> 27:25.280
There are others in front of you.

27:26.000 --> 27:27.280
The younger generation.

27:28.400 --> 27:30.160
You are madam, two teas.

27:30.160 --> 27:30.560
Sorry?

27:31.440 --> 27:32.160
What did you want?

27:33.040 --> 27:34.240
Two coffees.

27:34.240 --> 27:42.880
Excuse me, Mrs Britton.

27:42.880 --> 27:45.840
My name's Michael Trumpleton from the Stratford Gazette.

27:45.840 --> 27:48.480
Oh, the newspaper.

27:48.480 --> 27:50.560
Oh, yes, how lovely to meet you.

27:51.520 --> 27:53.280
Oh, please call me Nancy.

27:53.280 --> 27:55.760
Oh, yes, how lovely to meet you.

27:55.760 --> 27:57.360
Nice to meet you, Nancy.

27:57.360 --> 28:00.640
Come and sit down here and my husband will get you a pot of tea.

28:00.640 --> 28:02.640
Help himself to some biscuits.

28:02.640 --> 28:05.360
If your husband's the man in the rather uncomfortable tights,

28:05.360 --> 28:07.680
then I think he's rather busy at the moment.

28:07.680 --> 28:09.840
So you've met him already?

28:09.840 --> 28:12.000
Yes, he likes them like that.

28:16.000 --> 28:17.920
Oh, wow, these are super.

28:20.640 --> 28:22.000
Better than my mum's cooking.

28:22.720 --> 28:23.360
Thank you.

28:23.920 --> 28:25.360
It's my own recipe.

28:26.080 --> 28:28.880
Perhaps you could give me a list of the ingredients.

28:28.880 --> 28:31.520
It would be good to put it into the newspaper article.

28:31.600 --> 28:32.720
Yes, of course.

28:33.520 --> 28:35.360
It's very simple, really.

28:35.360 --> 28:40.640
Just flour, butter, nutmeg, some milk and, um, eggs.

28:40.640 --> 28:41.920
I think that's all.

28:41.920 --> 28:43.920
Oh, yes, and lemon juice.

28:43.920 --> 28:44.720
Thank you.

28:44.720 --> 28:46.720
I know you're all very busy at the moment,

28:46.720 --> 28:49.440
but could I have a photo of you all in front of the shop?

28:49.440 --> 28:50.800
Of course you can.

28:51.440 --> 28:56.240
Mum, Josie, Pete, can you come here a moment, please?

28:56.240 --> 28:58.480
The newspaper wanted photo of us.

28:59.200 --> 28:59.920
Coming.

29:00.000 --> 29:02.400
Oh, how exciting.

29:02.400 --> 29:03.680
What now?

29:03.680 --> 29:05.760
Yes, now, please, Pete.

29:06.480 --> 29:08.320
Oh, what a life.

29:08.320 --> 29:10.560
Just help yourself, everyone.

29:10.560 --> 29:11.760
Be careful with the kettle.

29:11.760 --> 29:12.560
It's very hot.

29:13.200 --> 29:15.040
Wouldn't want you to burn yourself.

29:15.840 --> 29:18.080
Yes, madam, that is Darjeeling tea.

29:18.080 --> 29:19.760
It's written on the packet.

29:19.760 --> 29:21.280
D-A-R.

29:21.280 --> 29:22.240
Heat.

29:22.240 --> 29:23.840
I'm coming, I'm coming.

29:30.240 --> 29:33.760
APPLAUSE

29:33.760 --> 29:36.160
Can you all stand in front of the shop, please?

29:36.160 --> 29:37.520
Thank you, that's fine.

29:38.080 --> 29:40.000
Rather strange spelling on the shop sign,

29:40.640 --> 29:42.720
I thought the word Shakespeare had a piece.

29:42.720 --> 29:44.640
And my husband can explain that.

29:44.640 --> 29:45.840
Can't you, dear?

29:45.840 --> 29:47.040
Don't start again.

29:47.040 --> 29:49.360
I thought the topic was closed.

29:49.360 --> 29:49.840
Smile.

29:51.040 --> 29:52.400
And just one more picture.

29:53.680 --> 29:54.960
Thank you very much.

29:54.960 --> 29:57.520
The article should be in the newspaper next week.

29:57.520 --> 29:58.800
Nice to meet you.

29:58.800 --> 30:00.080
Come again soon.

30:00.080 --> 30:00.960
Goodbye, Nancy.

30:00.960 --> 30:02.080
Goodbye, Michael.

30:03.200 --> 30:04.240
Mm.

30:04.800 --> 30:06.160
Michael, is it?

30:06.160 --> 30:07.920
Friend of yours, is he?

30:07.920 --> 30:08.320
No.

30:08.880 --> 30:11.680
He's just a nice, polite young man, that's all.

30:12.960 --> 30:15.520
Anyway, can't stand here chatting all day.

30:15.520 --> 30:16.480
Come on, everyone.

30:16.480 --> 30:17.600
Back into the shop.

30:17.600 --> 30:18.560
There's work to do.

30:22.800 --> 30:23.680
Huh?

30:23.680 --> 30:25.600
I forgot the baking powder.

30:25.600 --> 30:27.120
I bought it yesterday,

30:27.120 --> 30:28.000
don't you remember?

30:28.000 --> 30:28.960
Yes, I know.

30:28.960 --> 30:31.120
But I forgot to tell Michael.

30:31.120 --> 30:31.440
Who?

30:32.720 --> 30:34.240
The journalist.

30:34.240 --> 30:36.320
He asked me for a recipe.

30:36.320 --> 30:39.040
I forgot to mention the baking powder.

30:39.040 --> 30:40.560
It's not important, is it?

30:40.560 --> 30:42.080
Of course it's important.

30:42.080 --> 30:43.360
Without the baking powder,

30:43.360 --> 30:45.120
there'll be as flat as a pancake.

30:45.120 --> 30:46.480
Don't worry so much.

30:47.120 --> 30:49.200
I think you should keep an eye on your mother.

30:49.200 --> 30:50.800
She's been at the Sherry trifle,

30:50.800 --> 30:53.200
and I think she's about to start singing.

30:53.200 --> 30:54.640
Oh, no.

30:54.640 --> 30:57.680
Oh, my darling, it's harder, Bob.

31:02.880 --> 31:04.640
Tourists from the USA.

31:08.480 --> 31:09.600
Come on, Sharon.

31:09.600 --> 31:10.640
You must see this.

31:11.440 --> 31:14.960
It's so quaint and so English.

31:14.960 --> 31:16.640
First must take some photos.

31:17.120 --> 31:18.480
It's lovely.

31:19.040 --> 31:20.240
Come on, babe.

31:20.240 --> 31:23.760
I want to try some of those lovely little English cakes.

31:23.840 --> 31:25.520
I could eat an elephant right now.

31:26.480 --> 31:28.720
It's so cute in here.

31:29.440 --> 31:32.160
And look what the waitresses are wearing.

31:32.160 --> 31:34.480
Just like in the movies.

31:35.440 --> 31:37.760
There's a table by the fireplace.

31:37.760 --> 31:38.080
Quick.

31:39.440 --> 31:39.920
Grand.

31:40.880 --> 31:44.480
Look, two Americans next to the fireplace.

31:44.480 --> 31:47.840
Oh, she's so big she needs two chairs.

31:48.560 --> 31:50.720
And he's got a Simpsons t-shirt on.

31:51.680 --> 31:53.360
This is going to be fun.

31:53.360 --> 31:54.720
Just watch me, Grand.

31:54.720 --> 31:57.200
What are you going to do, you watch?

32:00.000 --> 32:03.440
Welcome to our famous Shakespearean t-shop.

32:03.440 --> 32:07.040
It is indeed an honor to welcome you to our fine establishment.

32:07.600 --> 32:09.360
What sustenance can I provide?

32:10.240 --> 32:11.200
How did you say?

32:12.000 --> 32:13.360
Are you talking English?

32:14.240 --> 32:16.080
Of course he is, dear.

32:17.120 --> 32:19.200
Don't take any notice of him.

32:19.760 --> 32:22.480
I just love your Kuwait accent.

32:22.480 --> 32:25.040
It gives me goose, people.

32:25.040 --> 32:27.600
We want to try everything.

32:27.600 --> 32:30.320
Bring us a piece of everything.

32:30.320 --> 32:32.720
How you are so terrible, Tom.

32:32.720 --> 32:33.920
That's too much.

32:34.800 --> 32:37.840
We want to both start with your Caesar cream tea

32:37.840 --> 32:39.760
with lots of extra cream.

32:40.960 --> 32:44.240
Why not try the William Walnut Buns?

32:44.240 --> 32:47.840
A secret recipe was handed down through our family,

32:47.840 --> 32:49.280
the Shakespeare's.

32:49.280 --> 32:52.640
Sure thing, far of those as well.

32:52.640 --> 32:57.520
What do you mean, secret recipe was handed down through our family?

32:58.240 --> 33:01.360
Do you mean that you're related to Willy's Shakespeare?

33:02.480 --> 33:05.760
Yes, but don't tell everyone, please.

33:06.320 --> 33:08.560
We don't like to tell too many people.

33:08.560 --> 33:11.440
Oh, you English are so reserved.

33:11.440 --> 33:14.560
I promise we won't tell anyone.

33:14.560 --> 33:17.360
All right then, I can tell you.

33:17.360 --> 33:18.800
What? What?

33:20.640 --> 33:24.400
William Shakespeare's my father's great-grandfather.

33:24.960 --> 33:27.040
Did you hear that, Sharon?

33:27.040 --> 33:28.080
Her father is...

33:28.080 --> 33:30.160
That's so well, Tom, dear.

33:31.360 --> 33:33.600
That's so awesome.

33:33.600 --> 33:37.040
Yes, and he's here in the shop at the moment.

33:37.920 --> 33:41.680
Wow, well, over there behind the counter.

33:41.680 --> 33:45.600
Oh yeah, he even looks like Willy Shakespeare.

33:45.600 --> 33:46.960
Don't you think, babe?

33:47.040 --> 33:50.080
I must have a photo for the folks back home.

33:50.080 --> 33:52.080
We must introduce ourselves.

33:52.080 --> 33:53.200
Come on, babe.

33:53.200 --> 33:55.520
Oh, don't tell him I said anything.

33:55.520 --> 33:55.920
Promise?

33:56.880 --> 33:57.920
Mom's the word.

33:58.640 --> 34:00.000
And one other thing.

34:01.520 --> 34:04.400
He is a close personal friend of the Queen,

34:05.040 --> 34:07.760
so please bow when you speak to him.

34:07.760 --> 34:10.400
This is so exciting!

34:10.400 --> 34:13.120
People back home simply won't believe us.

34:14.080 --> 34:17.280
Good morning, your royal highness.

34:17.280 --> 34:22.160
Love all, trust few, do wrong to none.

34:22.160 --> 34:23.920
Great lines.

34:23.920 --> 34:25.520
Uh, sorry.

34:25.520 --> 34:27.120
Sorry, sir.

34:27.120 --> 34:28.880
Shakes, be here.

34:28.880 --> 34:32.880
We're Sharon and Tom Jordan from Houston, Texas

34:32.880 --> 34:36.800
in the wonderful United States of America.

34:37.760 --> 34:38.960
Are you all right?

34:38.960 --> 34:39.920
Are you all right?

34:39.920 --> 34:43.440
Oh, you certainly are your royal-ness.

34:43.440 --> 34:43.680
Why?

34:44.640 --> 34:44.880
What?

34:46.080 --> 34:47.760
Do you both have a background?

34:48.640 --> 34:49.680
No, so Willy.

34:50.880 --> 34:55.520
I have wondered if I could have a photo of you standing with my Tom.

34:56.080 --> 34:58.640
For the people back home, you understand?

34:59.280 --> 35:03.120
Yes, but why are you bending over all the time?

35:03.120 --> 35:04.800
Go on, Tom, dear.

35:04.800 --> 35:06.560
Stand next to so Willy.

35:06.560 --> 35:07.200
Yes, dear.

35:08.160 --> 35:09.680
Love the clothes, Sir Willy.

35:09.680 --> 35:12.400
Ah, yes, I can explain that.

35:12.400 --> 35:14.000
They are not my idea.

35:14.000 --> 35:16.000
Please tell me, Sir Willy,

35:16.000 --> 35:18.640
after when you're next at the palace,

35:19.200 --> 35:21.120
we'd love an invitation to meet...

35:21.680 --> 35:22.480
You know who?

35:23.440 --> 35:25.360
Perhaps you could mention our names.

35:26.000 --> 35:28.320
Say that we like riding horses too.

35:29.200 --> 35:31.680
We also eat their health food jam.

35:32.320 --> 35:34.320
We get them in the States now.

35:34.320 --> 35:36.160
We love the raspberry jam.

35:36.160 --> 35:38.640
But not crazy about the gooseberry.

35:38.640 --> 35:40.160
The seeds get under my teeth.

35:40.960 --> 35:42.560
Sorry, do you need a doctor?

35:42.560 --> 35:44.640
Or maybe a psychiatrist?

35:44.640 --> 35:45.840
There's a good one in the village.

35:46.400 --> 35:47.440
Smile!

35:47.440 --> 35:48.720
Say cheese!

35:50.000 --> 35:51.520
Thank you, Sir Willy.

35:51.520 --> 35:52.720
My pleasure, but...

35:52.720 --> 35:54.080
By the way.

35:54.080 --> 35:54.960
Yes?

35:54.960 --> 35:56.960
We love your plays,

35:56.960 --> 35:58.720
and especially the movie.

35:59.600 --> 36:00.800
What's it called, babe?

36:00.800 --> 36:02.720
Um, it's on the tip of my tongue.

36:03.680 --> 36:05.760
Shakespeare, uh, uh, um...

36:05.760 --> 36:09.360
No, uh, Anda, uh, uh...

36:09.360 --> 36:10.480
In love?

36:10.480 --> 36:10.960
Sorry.

36:12.000 --> 36:14.400
We're married 28 years now.

36:14.400 --> 36:18.080
I suppose you could call it love, but it changes.

36:18.080 --> 36:20.880
The cost of true love never did run smooth.

36:21.840 --> 36:23.280
No, Sharon, dear.

36:23.280 --> 36:26.560
Sir Shakespeare is not asking about our marriage.

36:26.560 --> 36:28.560
He gave you the title of the film.

36:28.560 --> 36:30.160
Shakespeare in love?

36:30.800 --> 36:33.760
Ah, so how stupid I am!

36:33.920 --> 36:35.520
But tell me, sir, at...

36:36.080 --> 36:38.240
Why didn't you get Johnny Depp to do it?

36:38.240 --> 36:39.440
Much better actor.

36:39.440 --> 36:40.880
What are you talking about?

36:40.880 --> 36:41.760
Come on, dear.

36:42.400 --> 36:44.720
Thank you, Sir Shakespeare.

36:44.720 --> 36:46.160
Yes, you're right, dear.

36:46.160 --> 36:47.760
Thanks a bunch, Sir Willy.

36:48.320 --> 36:52.160
Going to try one or two of your secret willy walnut bones.

36:52.160 --> 36:52.560
Bye!

36:54.960 --> 36:55.840
Bloody Americans.

36:56.400 --> 36:59.440
Why didn't Christopher Columbus stay at home by the fire?

36:59.440 --> 37:01.360
Then he wouldn't have discovered America.

37:04.640 --> 37:10.640
Oh, did you enjoy your little chat?

37:10.640 --> 37:13.680
Very much, but I think he was a little confused.

37:14.800 --> 37:16.400
Excuse me, dear.

37:16.400 --> 37:19.120
Can you tell me where the rest room is?

37:19.760 --> 37:23.360
If you mean the toilets, they're outside at the bottom of the garden.

37:23.360 --> 37:23.840
What?

37:24.400 --> 37:25.360
They're in the garden?

37:26.000 --> 37:27.280
I have to see these.

37:27.280 --> 37:31.040
Yes, and they're the same as in William Shakespeare's day.

37:31.120 --> 37:35.520
Do you mean that Willy Shakespeare actually sat on your toilets?

37:35.520 --> 37:36.080
Oh, yes.

37:36.720 --> 37:39.680
He lived here as a child before he went to Stratford.

37:39.680 --> 37:40.880
Come on, babe.

37:40.880 --> 37:43.280
We must sit on the toilet.

37:43.280 --> 37:44.960
Feel where Willy sat.

37:44.960 --> 37:46.800
I'm coming with you, dear.

37:46.800 --> 37:48.400
I can't miss this.

37:54.160 --> 37:55.920
I heard that, Josie.

37:56.560 --> 37:58.960
You are so naughty.

37:58.960 --> 38:02.400
Well, Americans can be so stupid.

38:02.400 --> 38:03.520
They believe anything.

38:04.720 --> 38:07.600
What is the matter with those two Americans?

38:07.600 --> 38:09.680
I think they both have a screw loose.

38:09.680 --> 38:12.160
I have no idea what they were talking about.

38:12.720 --> 38:14.880
Yes, they are a little strange.

38:15.840 --> 38:17.440
I don't know why, Dad.

38:17.440 --> 38:18.080
No idea.

38:18.880 --> 38:19.840
No idea at all.

38:19.840 --> 38:20.480
Oh.

38:27.120 --> 38:28.320
Josie's revenge.

38:33.360 --> 38:35.040
Just look at this, everyone.

38:35.040 --> 38:36.000
It's wonderful.

38:36.000 --> 38:38.880
Oh, we're on the front page.

38:38.880 --> 38:39.760
Look, Josie.

38:41.360 --> 38:41.760
Nice.

38:43.760 --> 38:44.960
Yes, you're right.

38:44.960 --> 38:47.360
It's really good publicity for the tea shop.

38:48.080 --> 38:51.280
I hope we get more people coming in than the last few days.

38:51.280 --> 38:53.520
Don't worry so much, dear.

38:53.520 --> 38:55.120
I do worry.

38:55.120 --> 38:56.080
I worry a lot.

38:56.640 --> 38:58.000
I don't think that...

38:58.000 --> 39:01.840
It says here that the tea and cakes are delicious

39:01.840 --> 39:04.240
and the atmosphere is truly old-fashioned.

39:04.880 --> 39:07.440
And then he finishes the article with some comment

39:07.440 --> 39:10.320
that the owners are a bunch of real individuals

39:10.320 --> 39:13.760
who reflect the eccentricities of English village life.

39:14.720 --> 39:16.160
What exactly does it mean?

39:16.720 --> 39:17.760
It's an insult.

39:18.880 --> 39:20.480
He could have taken a better photo.

39:20.960 --> 39:22.240
I like it.

39:22.240 --> 39:24.240
Yes, well, you look lovely in it.

39:25.360 --> 39:28.640
Why are you holding a plate of donuts in front of you like that?

39:29.200 --> 39:30.560
Why do you think?

39:30.560 --> 39:32.880
Yes, but it does look a bit peculiar

39:32.880 --> 39:35.760
with a plate and two donuts down there.

39:36.320 --> 39:37.520
It looks as if you...

39:37.520 --> 39:38.960
Yes, thank you.

39:38.960 --> 39:39.840
Come on, Nancy.

39:39.840 --> 39:40.800
Back to work.

39:40.800 --> 39:42.480
The shop opens in 30 minutes.

39:42.720 --> 39:43.760
Shh.

39:44.800 --> 39:45.760
Gran.

39:45.760 --> 39:47.040
Yes, Josephine.

39:48.160 --> 39:52.320
Why is everyone talking about this bloody sodding tea shop?

39:52.320 --> 39:53.840
Yes, I'm no love.

39:53.840 --> 39:56.640
But the only bleeding topic is recipes for cakes.

39:57.440 --> 40:00.080
Shall we have dark peeling or not rain?

40:00.080 --> 40:03.760
I think it's dark jiggling and oh, grey, Josephine.

40:04.240 --> 40:05.920
Or who came into the shop?

40:06.640 --> 40:09.760
Do you know that Mrs. Snotface came in yesterday

40:09.760 --> 40:10.720
and she had two.

40:10.720 --> 40:13.120
Yes, two slices of big, well-taught.

40:15.920 --> 40:17.040
Very good, Josie.

40:17.040 --> 40:18.080
Very good.

40:18.080 --> 40:19.760
I'm not trying to be funny, Gran.

40:20.800 --> 40:23.920
And mum and dad seem to think I should always help in the shop.

40:24.880 --> 40:27.600
No, I don't have any free time to meet my friends.

40:27.600 --> 40:31.200
And every time I ask mum about how much she's going to pay me,

40:31.200 --> 40:34.160
she says, we can talk about it later.

40:34.160 --> 40:36.000
Shall I speak to your mother?

40:36.000 --> 40:36.800
Thanks, Gran.

40:37.680 --> 40:38.640
That would be great.

40:40.240 --> 40:42.400
Gran, yes, Josie.

40:43.680 --> 40:44.480
Can you help me?

40:45.040 --> 40:45.920
Of course.

40:46.560 --> 40:47.440
What can I do?

40:48.800 --> 40:51.920
Well, I want to play a joke on mum and dad.

40:53.360 --> 40:54.720
I like jokes.

40:55.520 --> 40:56.400
What do you mean?

40:56.960 --> 41:01.520
Put salt in the sugar bowl or unscrew the door handles?

41:02.160 --> 41:03.040
No, Gran.

41:04.000 --> 41:06.160
Tie their shoelaces together.

41:06.960 --> 41:10.080
Gran, something much more subtle.

41:10.080 --> 41:11.280
What do you want to do?

41:12.880 --> 41:18.880
Well, uh, I could phone up and pretend to be a health inspector.

41:19.680 --> 41:20.880
Why would you do that?

41:21.520 --> 41:22.560
None of us are ill.

41:23.520 --> 41:25.200
My back aches a bit.

41:25.200 --> 41:27.360
I have some problems in the night.

41:27.360 --> 41:29.760
No, Gran, you don't understand.

41:30.560 --> 41:33.360
A health inspector for the tea shop, not for you.

41:34.160 --> 41:35.280
Oh, I see.

41:36.480 --> 41:37.440
No, I don't.

41:37.440 --> 41:43.440
Gran, a health inspector comes and checks the kitchens to see if they are clean.

41:43.440 --> 41:46.720
But the kitchen is sparkless, I clean it myself.

41:46.720 --> 41:47.920
Yes, I know it is.

41:48.640 --> 41:51.280
But mum and dad will be frantic with worry,

41:51.280 --> 41:53.200
and they'll get so stressed out.

41:53.920 --> 41:54.720
It'll be fun.

41:55.440 --> 41:56.320
I don't know.

41:57.200 --> 41:58.400
Well, I want to try.

42:00.400 --> 42:02.720
What name should I use when I phone up?

42:02.720 --> 42:05.200
Are you really sure about this, Josie?

42:05.200 --> 42:06.160
Yes, I am.

42:07.040 --> 42:08.960
I think a man's voice is better.

42:08.960 --> 42:09.600
Let me try.

42:11.440 --> 42:12.560
Good afternoon, madam.

42:13.120 --> 42:14.880
My name is Mr. Chumley.

42:16.960 --> 42:19.200
Oh, that's very good, Josie.

42:19.200 --> 42:20.800
Come on, let me try.

42:21.440 --> 42:23.920
Oh, I'll go outside and use my mobile.

42:32.720 --> 42:39.200
Can you answer the phone, peatime busy?

42:40.000 --> 42:43.360
So am I, but that doesn't seem to be important.

42:43.360 --> 42:49.040
And if it's Mr. Chatterly wanting to come and discuss having afternoon tea for his society members,

42:49.040 --> 42:51.120
tell him any time is all right.

42:51.120 --> 42:51.840
Yes, dear.

42:53.600 --> 42:56.080
The old Shakespeare tea shop, how can I help you?

42:56.880 --> 42:58.640
Good afternoon, sir.

42:58.640 --> 43:02.080
Mr. Chumley, health inspector service speaking.

43:02.160 --> 43:05.600
Ah, yes, my wife said you, my phone.

43:05.600 --> 43:11.040
Yes, it's just an informal visit to have a look around in the next few days.

43:11.040 --> 43:12.640
No need to worry, sir.

43:12.640 --> 43:15.920
My wife said that any time this week is fine.

43:15.920 --> 43:17.040
Thank you, goodbye.

43:17.840 --> 43:18.560
Goodbye, sir.

43:22.000 --> 43:24.480
You were marvellous, Josie.

43:24.480 --> 43:26.160
Yes, I was good, wasn't I?

43:26.160 --> 43:28.320
Do you think they believed you?

43:28.320 --> 43:29.440
I don't know.

43:29.440 --> 43:33.520
Dad answered the phone, so I'm sure he'll get the message wrong when he tells mum.

43:33.520 --> 43:37.120
And then they will argue, oh, you are naughty.

43:43.040 --> 43:44.800
That was a bit strange.

43:44.800 --> 43:46.080
What's the matter?

43:46.080 --> 43:50.080
He had a peculiar voice, sounded familiar.

43:50.080 --> 43:52.240
Was it Mr. Chatterly on the phone?

43:52.240 --> 43:53.680
I think so, but...

43:53.680 --> 43:54.720
Yes?

43:54.720 --> 43:58.000
Is Mr. Chatterly from the health inspector service?

43:58.160 --> 43:59.120
Sorry.

43:59.760 --> 44:00.560
Hi.

44:00.560 --> 44:02.960
He said he was coming to check everything is okay.

44:04.000 --> 44:04.320
What?

44:05.360 --> 44:06.720
Health inspector?

44:06.720 --> 44:07.120
Here.

44:08.080 --> 44:11.760
Mr. Chatterly is chairman of the Marrow and Cucumber Society.

44:11.760 --> 44:13.440
He's not a health inspector.

44:13.440 --> 44:14.160
But...

44:14.160 --> 44:14.960
But Pete?

44:15.680 --> 44:18.560
If you had a brain, you would be dangerous.

44:20.080 --> 44:22.240
Is there anything between your ears?

44:22.240 --> 44:23.680
I don't understand.

44:23.680 --> 44:25.840
Why didn't I answer the phone?

44:25.840 --> 44:28.320
Why didn't you let me answer the phone?

44:28.320 --> 44:29.760
Sometimes...

44:29.760 --> 44:30.880
But you told...

44:32.560 --> 44:33.760
It doesn't matter, dear.

44:38.240 --> 44:38.880
Problems.

44:45.200 --> 44:46.320
What are you doing, dear?

44:47.120 --> 44:49.520
What are all these bills on the table?

44:49.520 --> 44:50.080
Look at this.

44:50.960 --> 44:51.440
And this.

44:52.320 --> 44:53.360
How much?

44:53.360 --> 44:55.120
I can't believe it.

44:55.120 --> 44:55.760
Look at this one.

44:57.440 --> 44:59.840
The insurance for the shop costs more than the value

44:59.840 --> 45:01.760
of a Manchester United football club.

45:02.320 --> 45:04.320
Don't exaggerate, Pete.

45:04.320 --> 45:07.040
There just aren't enough customers coming into the shop.

45:07.040 --> 45:08.480
We can't pay the bills.

45:09.040 --> 45:12.160
I think it was a bad idea to open a t-shop, Nancy.

45:12.800 --> 45:16.400
I think we have to close the shop down before it's too late.

45:16.400 --> 45:19.360
Oh, there must be an alternative.

45:19.360 --> 45:20.400
There isn't.

45:20.400 --> 45:20.880
Yes, but...

45:21.840 --> 45:24.160
We just have to work harder.

45:24.240 --> 45:26.880
It's not a question of working harder.

45:26.880 --> 45:28.400
We don't make enough money.

45:29.040 --> 45:31.280
Josie can't help any more than she does.

45:31.280 --> 45:33.440
She does have to go to school, Nancy.

45:33.440 --> 45:35.360
I know, I know.

45:35.360 --> 45:38.160
And we can't afford to have staff to support us.

45:38.160 --> 45:39.600
You and I are working all day,

45:39.600 --> 45:42.080
and sometimes it seems most of the night as well.

45:42.960 --> 45:44.720
And your mother does her best,

45:44.720 --> 45:46.640
but she's getting on in years,

45:46.640 --> 45:49.440
and you can't always rely on her.

45:49.440 --> 45:50.720
What do you mean?

45:50.720 --> 45:52.960
Well, look what happened yesterday.

45:53.520 --> 45:55.200
She got in a muddle with the orders,

45:55.200 --> 45:56.880
and one couple didn't pay,

45:56.880 --> 45:58.800
and another paid double.

45:58.800 --> 46:01.280
It was all sorted out eventually.

46:01.280 --> 46:02.240
Yes.

46:02.240 --> 46:04.800
Only after one couple phoned their solicitor,

46:04.800 --> 46:08.400
and I had to follow the Stratford bus in my car to catch the other couple.

46:09.520 --> 46:12.560
Do you know how many stops there are between here and Stratford?

46:12.560 --> 46:14.080
Do you know how many?

46:14.080 --> 46:15.680
No, I don't.

46:15.680 --> 46:16.640
27!

46:17.280 --> 46:18.320
27!

46:19.600 --> 46:20.560
And when I found them,

46:20.560 --> 46:22.800
it turned out that they had paid your mother.

46:22.800 --> 46:25.440
She had put the money in her pocket and forgotten about it.

46:26.240 --> 46:28.640
I mean, she drives me crazy.

46:29.600 --> 46:31.680
What do you suggest we do?

46:31.680 --> 46:35.680
Well, we could set fire to the shop and claim on the insurance.

46:36.320 --> 46:38.320
You're not serious, are you?

46:38.320 --> 46:39.600
What do you think?

46:39.600 --> 46:41.200
Of course I'm not serious.

46:43.200 --> 46:44.720
But it's an idea, then.

46:44.720 --> 46:46.720
Oh.

46:50.080 --> 46:51.200
Hello, Mum.

46:51.200 --> 46:51.920
You Josie.

46:52.960 --> 46:54.000
Can you both come here?

46:54.000 --> 46:55.120
We need to talk.

46:59.040 --> 47:01.600
I think we have to close down the shop.

47:02.640 --> 47:03.200
No!

47:04.080 --> 47:04.640
Why?

47:05.760 --> 47:06.880
It's such fun!

47:08.640 --> 47:10.800
I think I'm going to cry.

47:10.800 --> 47:13.760
Please don't probably strangle you if you do.

47:14.720 --> 47:16.560
Just listen to Pete, everyone.

47:18.000 --> 47:21.360
The simple fact is that we are losing money fast.

47:21.360 --> 47:25.120
There just aren't enough tourists coming in and the locals don't spend enough.

47:25.120 --> 47:26.240
Yes, you're right.

47:27.200 --> 47:32.880
Most tables are filled by old ladies who sit there all morning with one cup of tea and a fruit bun.

47:34.000 --> 47:38.320
Sometimes I see them getting their own biscuits and cakes out of their shopping bags.

47:39.360 --> 47:43.200
Perhaps we should body search all the customers as they come in the shop.

47:43.920 --> 47:47.360
Sometimes I wonder what goes on inside your mother's head, Nancy.

47:48.240 --> 47:50.800
Have you got any ideas, Josie?

47:50.800 --> 47:52.720
You're the intelligent one in the family.

47:55.760 --> 47:57.760
We need some promotions.

47:57.760 --> 47:59.440
I want to be promoted.

48:00.160 --> 48:02.160
I want to be the manager-ress.

48:02.160 --> 48:03.280
No, Gran.

48:03.280 --> 48:05.120
I don't mean that type of promotion.

48:05.920 --> 48:11.120
I mean, we need some new ideas to get people interested in coming into the shop.

48:11.200 --> 48:13.440
Oh, I see, silly me.

48:15.280 --> 48:22.560
Why don't I have a table outside the tea shop and I can sell some Shakespeare souvenirs

48:22.560 --> 48:27.280
and read out some famous Shakespeare sayings to get people to stop?

48:27.280 --> 48:28.800
That's a nice idea, Mum.

48:29.600 --> 48:31.360
I know what you can do, Dad.

48:32.000 --> 48:34.720
Am I going to like this idea or not?

48:35.440 --> 48:40.000
Well, you said that we aren't getting enough tourists in the shop.

48:40.080 --> 48:40.640
Yes.

48:41.600 --> 48:43.600
Where are all the tourists?

48:43.600 --> 48:45.920
In Stratford, perhaps?

48:45.920 --> 48:46.640
That's right.

48:47.600 --> 48:52.000
You and Boris can walk through Stratford giving out leaflets to all the tourists.

48:52.800 --> 48:55.760
Boris can wear something as well to look medieval.

48:55.760 --> 48:58.160
Any of your mother's clothes would be perfect, Nancy.

48:59.120 --> 49:02.160
You can have a 10% voucher on the leaflet, Dad.

49:03.040 --> 49:07.840
And you can carry a sandwich board with a big poster advertising the tea shop on it.

49:08.640 --> 49:10.800
You'll look great in your Shakespeare costume.

49:11.760 --> 49:16.800
You can read out bits of Shakespeare and have Elizabethan music playing in the background.

49:16.800 --> 49:19.520
Oh, I knew I wasn't going to like the idea.

49:20.560 --> 49:24.320
But desperate situations call for desperate measures.

49:25.040 --> 49:28.080
If we don't get more customers in the shop in the next couple of weeks,

49:28.080 --> 49:29.920
then we have to close.

49:29.920 --> 49:31.040
That's final.

49:31.920 --> 49:33.680
Come on then, everyone.

49:33.680 --> 49:35.520
Let's get started.

49:35.520 --> 49:37.040
No time to lose.

49:38.320 --> 49:38.880
What?

49:50.480 --> 49:51.760
Promoting the tea shop.

49:56.320 --> 49:57.760
What are you doing, Gran?

49:57.760 --> 50:02.000
I want to put some balloons on the table, make people stop and look.

50:05.200 --> 50:06.640
What do you think?

50:06.640 --> 50:09.680
It's a cool idea with the table in front of the shop.

50:09.680 --> 50:10.640
Oh, thank you.

50:13.680 --> 50:15.440
This is not so easy.

50:15.440 --> 50:15.840
Oops.

50:17.360 --> 50:20.000
I thought you wanted to sell Shakespeare's souvenirs.

50:20.560 --> 50:24.560
I'm not sure that your pink hand knitted bed socks are very Shakespearean.

50:25.840 --> 50:30.160
I'm going to tell people the knitting pattern is

50:32.480 --> 50:34.160
from Shakespeare's mother.

50:34.160 --> 50:36.320
So easy with the balloons, Gran.

50:36.320 --> 50:37.280
Don't overdo it.

50:38.800 --> 50:40.240
Oh, this is fun.

50:45.120 --> 50:45.760
Oh, dear.

50:48.080 --> 50:49.120
Oh, dear.

50:49.840 --> 50:51.280
I told you to be careful.

50:53.040 --> 50:54.960
Oh, I don't feel...

50:54.960 --> 50:56.320
Oh, Gran! Gran!

50:56.880 --> 50:58.240
Oh, no! What's the matter?

50:58.240 --> 50:59.200
Help! Someone!

50:59.840 --> 51:00.800
Help! Please!

51:01.680 --> 51:03.520
Mom! Dad! Help!

51:04.720 --> 51:05.760
What's the matter, Josie?

51:05.760 --> 51:06.480
It's Gran!

51:07.040 --> 51:08.320
She was blowing up balloons.

51:08.320 --> 51:10.480
I told her to stop, but she didn't.

51:10.480 --> 51:11.600
She's collapsed.

51:11.600 --> 51:12.720
I think she's dead.

51:12.720 --> 51:15.040
No, she's just fainted.

51:15.040 --> 51:16.000
Silly old fool.

51:16.720 --> 51:17.360
Leave it to me.

51:18.160 --> 51:19.360
What are you doing, Dad?

51:19.360 --> 51:20.560
Leave it to me.

51:20.560 --> 51:21.040
You see.

51:23.680 --> 51:25.360
No, Dad, don't do that.

51:26.800 --> 51:27.040
Oh!

51:28.720 --> 51:29.840
This always works.

51:29.840 --> 51:30.800
Come on, wake up.

51:31.440 --> 51:32.800
What's happening here?

51:34.800 --> 51:37.360
Mom, what are you doing, Pete?

51:37.360 --> 51:38.880
The old fool fainted.

51:38.880 --> 51:41.200
I just threw a jug of water over her.

51:41.200 --> 51:42.720
You idiot!

51:42.720 --> 51:44.080
Phone for an ambulance.

51:44.080 --> 51:47.040
But don't, as I tell you, now!

51:47.040 --> 51:47.840
All right.

51:47.840 --> 51:49.040
All right. I'm going.

51:49.680 --> 51:50.560
What a week.

52:00.640 --> 52:02.880
Oh, I feel a bit better now.

52:02.880 --> 52:04.800
Oh, what happened?

52:05.840 --> 52:06.720
I feel wet.

52:07.440 --> 52:09.360
You're all right now, Mom.

52:09.360 --> 52:10.960
The ambulance is here now.

52:10.960 --> 52:12.720
Everything's going to be all right.

52:13.920 --> 52:15.120
Come on, Boris.

52:15.120 --> 52:16.720
Let's drive to Stratford.

52:16.720 --> 52:20.320
I think it's better if we keep away from Nancy for a few hours.

52:20.320 --> 52:20.880
Don't you?

52:29.840 --> 52:31.840
What?

52:43.760 --> 52:45.200
Here we are, Boris.

52:45.200 --> 52:48.080
I hope we don't meet anyone we know in Stratford.

52:48.080 --> 52:50.560
We both look completely ridiculous.

52:53.280 --> 52:54.240
Love the tides, mate.

52:55.520 --> 52:57.360
I knew this wasn't a good idea.

52:58.160 --> 52:59.280
Come on, let's start.

53:00.160 --> 53:02.960
We can put some leaflets under the windscreen wipers.

53:02.960 --> 53:04.080
Good idea, eh?

53:06.000 --> 53:08.560
This sandwich board is so awkward and heavy.

53:09.120 --> 53:10.720
What a stupid idea, eh?

53:12.080 --> 53:13.040
What's the matter, Boris?

53:14.240 --> 53:16.000
Oh, it's a cat.

53:16.560 --> 53:18.160
No, it's not.

53:19.680 --> 53:20.640
Come back.

53:20.640 --> 53:22.720
Oh, the light caught around my legs.

53:22.720 --> 53:26.080
Oh, oh, oh, oh.

53:26.080 --> 53:27.440
Oh, my God.

53:27.440 --> 53:29.040
I'll be in the W.

53:29.040 --> 53:30.000
Right!

53:31.440 --> 53:32.400
Oops.

53:32.400 --> 53:33.440
That was a wing mirror.

53:33.440 --> 53:35.600
Just stop it, Boris.

53:35.600 --> 53:36.480
Calm down.

53:37.040 --> 53:38.000
Look what you've done.

53:38.560 --> 53:40.480
Come on, before anyone sees us.

53:45.280 --> 53:48.960
We can stand here outside marks and Spencer's, Boris.

53:49.600 --> 53:52.560
Just sit quietly and look sweet and cuddly.

53:52.960 --> 53:53.600
Please.

53:54.960 --> 53:56.960
Okay, here goes.

54:00.320 --> 54:04.080
The only Shakespeare tea shopping in wire piddle.

54:04.720 --> 54:09.680
Biscuits and cakes freshly baked using Shakespeare's own recipes.

54:10.720 --> 54:12.960
The alarm, Adam, please have a leaflet.

54:12.960 --> 54:13.840
Thank you very much.

54:14.560 --> 54:16.880
Visit Shakespeare's favorite tea shop.

54:17.440 --> 54:19.680
To be or not to be.

54:19.680 --> 54:21.120
That is the question.

54:22.080 --> 54:23.120
Thank you, sir.

54:23.120 --> 54:23.680
And, Adam.

54:24.320 --> 54:25.920
I like your dog.

54:25.920 --> 54:27.120
Yes, madam, thank you.

54:27.920 --> 54:29.840
The only Shakespeare tea.

54:29.840 --> 54:30.800
What is name?

54:31.360 --> 54:31.920
Sorry?

54:31.920 --> 54:32.160
What?

54:32.960 --> 54:33.760
It's Boris.

54:34.640 --> 54:36.400
The only Shakespeare...

54:36.400 --> 54:37.760
That's an old name.

54:37.760 --> 54:38.720
You should know.

54:38.720 --> 54:40.080
I heard that.

54:40.080 --> 54:42.480
Could you just go away, please, madam?

54:42.480 --> 54:45.920
I'm trying to advertise our world famous tea shop.

54:46.720 --> 54:50.800
The only Shakespeare tea shopping in wire piddle.

54:50.880 --> 54:53.520
Visit Shakespeare's favorite tea shop.

54:53.520 --> 54:56.720
Visit the house where he lived as a child.

54:56.720 --> 54:59.520
William Shakespeare never lived in wire piddle.

54:59.520 --> 55:01.360
Yes, he did.

55:01.360 --> 55:05.040
Before he went to a war.

55:05.760 --> 55:07.520
Before he went to war.

55:07.520 --> 55:08.640
No, he didn't.

55:08.640 --> 55:10.240
What are you talking about?

55:10.240 --> 55:14.400
Before he was called to the prompt.

55:15.040 --> 55:16.560
He never went to war.

55:16.560 --> 55:17.120
Yes, he did.

55:17.760 --> 55:18.880
It's before your time.

55:19.360 --> 55:20.960
But only just.

55:20.960 --> 55:22.880
You are talking complete rubbish.

55:22.880 --> 55:24.080
Just go away, madam.

55:24.960 --> 55:28.400
The only Shakespeare tea shopping in wire piddle.

55:28.400 --> 55:32.560
Traditional English tea shop with traditional homemade cakes.

55:32.560 --> 55:34.320
Here's a pamphlet for you, madam.

55:34.320 --> 55:34.880
Thank you.

55:35.520 --> 55:38.720
As William Shakespeare wrote in Macbeth,

55:38.720 --> 55:41.760
I have nothing to offer but blood.

55:41.760 --> 55:44.720
Oil, tears and sweat.

55:44.720 --> 55:46.880
William Shakespeare didn't write that.

55:46.880 --> 55:48.640
Winston Churchill wrote it.

55:48.640 --> 55:49.440
No, he didn't.

55:49.440 --> 55:50.400
Yes, he did.

55:50.400 --> 55:51.360
I should know.

55:51.360 --> 55:55.040
And why are you suddenly an expert on Shakespeare?

55:55.680 --> 55:58.240
I'm an historian from the local museum.

56:00.480 --> 56:02.240
Yes, well, aha.

56:02.240 --> 56:06.480
That William Shakespeare didn't actually write it.

56:06.480 --> 56:11.200
But Winston Churchill borrowed the idea from him.

56:12.240 --> 56:15.040
I can't stand here talking to you all day.

56:15.040 --> 56:15.920
Come on, Boris.

56:17.680 --> 56:20.960
Some people have no idea, do they, Boris?

56:22.800 --> 56:24.320
Winston Churchill.

56:24.880 --> 56:26.320
No idea.

56:27.120 --> 56:30.000
Only another 900 leaflets to give out.

56:30.000 --> 56:33.760
Come on, let's get on with this and then get back to the shop.

56:35.440 --> 56:39.360
The only Shakespeare tea shopping in wire piddle.

56:39.360 --> 56:43.520
Traditional English tea shop with traditional homemade cakes.

56:44.320 --> 56:47.840
Here's a leaflet for you, sir, and your lovely daughter.

56:47.840 --> 56:48.880
Thank you.

56:48.880 --> 56:51.280
Hope to see both of you in our tea shop.

56:52.880 --> 56:57.120
The only Shakespeare tea shopping in wire piddle.

56:57.120 --> 57:01.040
As Shakespeare said himself on his death bed,

57:01.040 --> 57:03.920
never in the field of human conflict.

57:03.920 --> 57:06.000
Winston Churchill said that as well.

57:06.000 --> 57:07.680
It wasn't Shakespeare.

57:07.680 --> 57:09.120
Leave me alone.

57:09.120 --> 57:12.160
Go to speaker's corner and annoy some people there.

57:13.520 --> 57:14.640
What a terrible woman.

57:15.280 --> 57:17.200
She has no idea at all.

57:17.920 --> 57:19.360
I can't believe that.

57:21.200 --> 57:22.640
A special visit.

57:25.760 --> 57:27.120
Never again.

57:27.120 --> 57:28.800
What's the matter now?

57:28.800 --> 57:31.360
Everywhere I went, she was there.

57:31.360 --> 57:33.520
Called herself an historian.

57:33.520 --> 57:36.880
She had no idea, no idea at all.

57:36.880 --> 57:37.840
Yes, dear.

57:37.840 --> 57:42.080
You've told me the same story at least 10 times since breakfast.

57:42.080 --> 57:43.120
Yeah, I mean.

57:43.120 --> 57:44.480
You can't complain.

57:45.120 --> 57:48.000
I think we've had at least 20 new customers so far.

57:48.640 --> 57:49.520
Excuse me.

57:49.520 --> 57:50.640
You over there.

57:50.640 --> 57:51.840
Come here, please.

57:51.840 --> 57:53.120
Are you referring to me?

57:53.120 --> 57:54.480
Yes, you will.

57:54.480 --> 57:57.040
I thought slavery had been abolished.

57:57.040 --> 57:59.920
Try to be more polite to the customer's peat.

57:59.920 --> 58:01.120
Yes, dear.

58:01.120 --> 58:02.000
Yes, dear.

58:02.960 --> 58:04.640
How can I help you, madam?

58:04.640 --> 58:06.640
This is not a proper scone.

58:06.640 --> 58:07.760
What are these?

58:07.760 --> 58:10.000
I believe in the catering world.

58:10.000 --> 58:12.880
They are usually called sultanas, madam.

58:12.880 --> 58:14.880
Maybe you haven't heard of them before.

58:14.880 --> 58:16.320
Don't be so stupid.

58:17.040 --> 58:20.080
I want you to take this away and bring me another scone

58:20.080 --> 58:21.760
without sultanas.

58:21.760 --> 58:24.080
Of course, madam, whatever you say.

58:24.080 --> 58:27.600
Would you also like the strawberries removed from the strawberry jam?

58:28.160 --> 58:29.040
No, thank you.

58:29.040 --> 58:30.320
The jam is fine.

58:30.320 --> 58:32.160
Well, I'm pleased to hear that.

58:33.840 --> 58:34.880
But sure.

58:34.880 --> 58:36.560
The people we get in here.

58:36.560 --> 58:38.000
What's the matter now?

58:38.640 --> 58:42.880
Queen Victoria at Table Six wants a scone without sultanas.

58:42.880 --> 58:44.640
I'm just making some more.

58:44.640 --> 58:46.960
I can make some without sultanas.

58:46.960 --> 58:48.160
Thank you, Mum.

58:48.160 --> 58:49.120
You see, Pete?

58:49.120 --> 58:50.880
You shouldn't get so stressed.

58:50.880 --> 58:52.320
I'm not stressed.

58:52.320 --> 58:54.480
It's just the people we get in here.

58:55.600 --> 58:56.560
What are you doing?

58:56.560 --> 58:58.640
Don't put a knife in the mix of peat.

58:58.640 --> 59:00.080
I just want to try the...

59:02.720 --> 59:03.200
Bloody hell.

59:03.200 --> 59:05.200
No.

59:05.200 --> 59:07.680
Frank, why did you turn the mixer on?

59:07.680 --> 59:08.880
I didn't see you.

59:09.520 --> 59:11.440
Get out of the kitchen, Pete.

59:11.440 --> 59:12.960
God, I'm going.

59:14.320 --> 59:15.600
Good morning, sir.

59:15.600 --> 59:20.240
I'm a local health inspector and I want to inspect your premises, please.

59:20.240 --> 59:21.280
Yes, and I'm...

59:21.280 --> 59:24.960
I'm still waiting for my scone without sultanas.

59:24.960 --> 59:26.800
Just be quiet and wait.

59:26.800 --> 59:29.360
Do you always speak to your customers like that?

59:29.360 --> 59:29.920
No.

59:29.920 --> 59:32.480
Only the ones I would like deported to the continent.

59:33.200 --> 59:34.720
Now, who did you say you were?

59:34.720 --> 59:36.560
The local health inspector.

59:36.560 --> 59:38.240
Here to check your kitchen.

59:38.240 --> 59:40.400
Yes, wonderful.

59:41.920 --> 59:44.400
Yes, that's all we need.

59:44.400 --> 59:46.000
Are you feeling all right?

59:46.000 --> 59:48.080
Yes, yes.

59:48.080 --> 59:50.160
Lovely day, isn't it?

59:50.720 --> 59:52.880
Pity about the cricket score.

59:53.920 --> 59:55.280
Please, just wait there.

59:56.480 --> 59:57.840
Meet to nice you.

59:57.840 --> 59:58.480
I mean...

59:58.480 --> 01:00:00.480
...and everyone.

01:00:01.760 --> 01:00:02.800
He's here.

01:00:03.200 --> 01:00:04.640
What are you talking about?

01:00:04.640 --> 01:00:05.760
Careful where you walk.

01:00:05.760 --> 01:00:06.480
Not there.

01:00:06.480 --> 01:00:07.680
He's here.

01:00:07.680 --> 01:00:09.360
Now look what you've done.

01:00:09.360 --> 01:00:10.720
The floor is slippery.

01:00:10.720 --> 01:00:12.080
Be careful.

01:00:12.080 --> 01:00:13.280
He's here.

01:00:13.280 --> 01:00:14.960
The man who phoned.

01:00:14.960 --> 01:00:16.800
Each man who phoned.

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:18.960
Oh, no.

01:00:18.960 --> 01:00:20.640
What the hell, Inspector?

01:00:20.640 --> 01:00:21.280
Yes.

01:00:21.280 --> 01:00:22.480
Don't let him come in here.

01:00:22.480 --> 01:00:23.520
Look at this mess.

01:00:23.520 --> 01:00:24.640
Give him in the shop.

01:00:24.640 --> 01:00:25.520
How?

01:00:25.520 --> 01:00:27.440
Use your imagination.

01:00:27.440 --> 01:00:28.320
Sing songs.

01:00:29.280 --> 01:00:30.080
Sing songs.

01:00:30.800 --> 01:00:32.720
Sing songs to him.

01:00:32.720 --> 01:00:34.880
Are you completely mad?

01:00:34.880 --> 01:00:36.080
What do you suggest?

01:00:36.080 --> 01:00:37.440
Handles Messiah.

01:00:37.440 --> 01:00:38.160
Make songs.

01:00:38.160 --> 01:00:39.920
Requiem might be more appropriate.

01:00:40.960 --> 01:00:44.000
Just do something, but get out of here.

01:00:48.960 --> 01:00:49.520
Hello.

01:00:50.640 --> 01:00:51.280
Where's he gone?

01:00:52.480 --> 01:00:53.680
Where's he gone?

01:00:53.680 --> 01:00:55.760
If you are referring to that gentleman,

01:00:55.760 --> 01:00:58.160
he's gone to inspect the sanitary arrangements.

01:01:00.240 --> 01:01:02.160
Just had a look at your toilets.

01:01:02.160 --> 01:01:04.640
I'm afraid it is forbidden to have outside

01:01:04.640 --> 01:01:06.400
toilets like those in a restaurant.

01:01:06.400 --> 01:01:07.040
But...

01:01:07.040 --> 01:01:07.760
But...

01:01:07.760 --> 01:01:09.920
I want to inspect your kitchen now, please.

01:01:10.640 --> 01:01:13.280
Maybe you would like a cup of tea first.

01:01:13.280 --> 01:01:14.480
No, thank you.

01:01:14.480 --> 01:01:15.840
Just your kitchen, please.

01:01:15.840 --> 01:01:17.280
I know we can...

01:01:18.640 --> 01:01:21.280
look at the flowers in the garden.

01:01:21.840 --> 01:01:23.520
Do you like flowers?

01:01:23.520 --> 01:01:25.280
Just the kitchen, please.

01:01:25.840 --> 01:01:27.520
It's through this door, isn't it?

01:01:27.520 --> 01:01:33.520
Maybe you would like to hear me sing.

01:01:34.400 --> 01:01:35.360
I beg your pardon.

01:01:35.920 --> 01:01:36.880
Stupid idea.

01:01:36.880 --> 01:01:38.160
It wasn't my idea.

01:01:41.440 --> 01:01:42.960
Good morning, madame.

01:01:42.960 --> 01:01:43.920
Whoa!

01:01:44.880 --> 01:01:46.640
Let me help you up.

01:01:46.640 --> 01:01:47.840
Sorry about that.

01:01:48.720 --> 01:01:50.960
Oh, perhaps you would like a scone.

01:01:51.520 --> 01:01:53.600
We're all without sultanas.

01:01:53.600 --> 01:01:54.640
No, thank you.

01:01:55.440 --> 01:01:57.040
What a mess in here.

01:01:57.040 --> 01:01:58.400
It's not acceptable.

01:01:59.360 --> 01:02:00.480
And what's that noise?

01:02:01.360 --> 01:02:03.200
It's coming from the cupboard over there.

01:02:03.200 --> 01:02:03.760
Let me see.

01:02:07.760 --> 01:02:10.240
There's a rat in a box in here.

01:02:10.240 --> 01:02:11.600
I'll kill her!

01:02:11.600 --> 01:02:13.040
Where is Josephine?

01:02:13.040 --> 01:02:14.240
Where is he?

01:02:14.240 --> 01:02:16.320
You must close this shop now.

01:02:16.320 --> 01:02:18.880
It's an absolute disgrace.

01:02:18.880 --> 01:02:20.640
I'll be writing a full report

01:02:20.640 --> 01:02:22.960
and you can expect a very heavy fine.

01:02:23.600 --> 01:02:24.720
Oh, no.

01:02:24.720 --> 01:02:26.160
It's the end.

01:02:28.720 --> 01:02:29.760
What's going on?

01:02:30.960 --> 01:02:32.080
Stop it, Pete.

01:02:32.080 --> 01:02:33.280
Don't be stupid.

01:02:33.280 --> 01:02:34.880
Come here, Josephine.

01:02:34.880 --> 01:02:35.840
What's happening here?

01:02:36.400 --> 01:02:37.600
Are you all going bonkers?

01:02:38.160 --> 01:02:39.120
And who are you?

01:02:39.120 --> 01:02:40.880
I'm the local health inspector

01:02:40.880 --> 01:02:43.280
and I'm closing this shop now.

01:02:43.280 --> 01:02:44.560
You can't be.

01:02:44.560 --> 01:02:45.440
It was a joke.

01:02:46.080 --> 01:02:48.320
It's not a joke, Josephine.

01:02:48.320 --> 01:02:50.160
He phoned a few days ago.

01:02:50.800 --> 01:02:51.680
That was me.

01:02:52.320 --> 01:02:54.480
I pretended to be the health inspector.

01:02:54.480 --> 01:02:55.600
It was a joke.

01:02:56.240 --> 01:02:57.520
What's happening here?

01:02:57.520 --> 01:02:59.280
What are you talking about?

01:02:59.280 --> 01:03:00.480
Ask Gran.

01:03:00.480 --> 01:03:01.360
She knows.

01:03:01.360 --> 01:03:02.160
Yes.

01:03:02.160 --> 01:03:04.960
I was there when Josie phoned you.

01:03:04.960 --> 01:03:07.360
She's very clever, isn't she?

01:03:07.360 --> 01:03:09.280
She should become an actress.

01:03:09.280 --> 01:03:11.680
Maybe a famous Hollywood actress

01:03:12.320 --> 01:03:13.600
in the films.

01:03:13.600 --> 01:03:15.760
But who are you?

01:03:17.040 --> 01:03:19.680
Have you asked him to show you his credentials?

01:03:19.680 --> 01:03:21.680
Oh, I must go now.

01:03:21.680 --> 01:03:23.600
I have another tea shop to visit.

01:03:23.600 --> 01:03:24.880
Don't forget what I said.

01:03:26.160 --> 01:03:27.360
Oh, hello, Trevor.

01:03:27.360 --> 01:03:28.320
What a surprise.

01:03:28.880 --> 01:03:30.960
Haven't seen you for a long time.

01:03:30.960 --> 01:03:31.680
How are you?

01:03:32.640 --> 01:03:34.080
Oh, hello, Si.

01:03:34.640 --> 01:03:35.520
Yes, I'm fine.

01:03:35.520 --> 01:03:35.920
Thanks.

01:03:36.960 --> 01:03:37.360
Goodbye.

01:03:40.480 --> 01:03:42.080
Strange man.

01:03:42.080 --> 01:03:43.120
What's all the noise?

01:03:43.120 --> 01:03:45.040
Julian and I were worried.

01:03:45.040 --> 01:03:46.080
What's happening in here?

01:03:46.640 --> 01:03:48.480
It's a terrible mess.

01:03:48.640 --> 01:03:50.560
The health inspector was here.

01:03:51.680 --> 01:03:52.320
When?

01:03:52.320 --> 01:03:52.800
Today?

01:03:53.520 --> 01:03:55.680
When you came in, you said hello.

01:03:55.680 --> 01:03:56.960
You must know him.

01:03:56.960 --> 01:03:57.840
Oh, yes.

01:03:57.840 --> 01:03:59.600
That's Trevor McMubble.

01:03:59.600 --> 01:04:01.360
He's an old school friend.

01:04:01.360 --> 01:04:03.440
I sometimes see him in Stratford.

01:04:03.440 --> 01:04:04.640
He ends a tea shop there.

01:04:05.440 --> 01:04:07.680
He owns a tea shop.

01:04:08.240 --> 01:04:09.680
But I don't understand.

01:04:10.240 --> 01:04:12.640
Why did he say he was a health inspector?

01:04:12.640 --> 01:04:16.320
Hmm, I think I'm beginning to understand.

01:04:16.960 --> 01:04:20.480
He's worried about the competition from our tea shop.

01:04:20.480 --> 01:04:22.720
Since I did my advertising in Stratford,

01:04:22.720 --> 01:04:24.000
we've had more customers.

01:04:24.640 --> 01:04:28.160
He wanted to frighten us and get us to close down.

01:04:29.200 --> 01:04:31.120
What a shock that was.

01:04:32.880 --> 01:04:34.640
What a horrible thing to do.

01:04:35.520 --> 01:04:37.440
Thank God, that's over and done with.

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:39.280
Come on, everybody.

01:04:39.280 --> 01:04:41.280
Let's have a nice cup of tea.

01:04:41.280 --> 01:04:41.680
Gran?

01:04:42.560 --> 01:04:45.360
I even like your scones without sultanas.

01:04:47.280 --> 01:04:48.320
Good afternoon.

01:04:48.960 --> 01:04:51.520
I'm from the Stratford Public Health Office.

01:04:51.520 --> 01:04:54.160
I've had reports that there are rats in this tea shop.

01:04:56.080 --> 01:04:58.560
Is this another friend of yours, Si?

01:04:59.120 --> 01:04:59.840
Sorry, love.

01:04:59.840 --> 01:05:00.720
You're too late.

01:05:00.720 --> 01:05:03.440
Oh, your friend was here one minute ago.

01:05:03.440 --> 01:05:04.720
We're not worried.

01:05:04.720 --> 01:05:06.240
But this is serious.

01:05:06.240 --> 01:05:08.800
If the reports are correct, I'll have to close this shop.

01:05:09.440 --> 01:05:10.960
I want to have a look around.

01:05:10.960 --> 01:05:12.800
Of course you do, madam.

01:05:12.800 --> 01:05:16.000
But you can't get out of our shop now.

01:05:16.080 --> 01:05:17.200
We know you're gay.

01:05:18.160 --> 01:05:19.040
Go on out.

01:05:19.040 --> 01:05:20.160
We don't believe you.

01:05:20.160 --> 01:05:21.440
You don't frighten us.

01:05:21.440 --> 01:05:22.080
It's my bet.

01:05:22.080 --> 01:05:23.280
What are you doing?

01:05:23.280 --> 01:05:24.800
Here's my identity card.

01:05:24.800 --> 01:05:26.720
Yes, of course it is.

01:05:27.440 --> 01:05:29.680
You have an identity card.

01:05:29.680 --> 01:05:31.520
What a surprise.

01:05:31.520 --> 01:05:33.680
Your partner in grind, didn't you?

01:05:33.680 --> 01:05:34.400
Let me see it.

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:39.200
Ah, Pete.

01:05:39.200 --> 01:05:39.680
Yes?

01:05:40.480 --> 01:05:43.840
I think you should look at this identity card.

01:05:44.640 --> 01:05:46.000
It's genuine.

01:05:47.280 --> 01:05:47.440
What?

01:05:48.400 --> 01:05:49.200
It can't be.

01:05:49.200 --> 01:05:49.760
Let me look.

01:05:53.920 --> 01:05:54.400
Oh no.

01:05:55.520 --> 01:05:56.560
The bat to hunt.

01:06:13.840 --> 01:06:15.840
You

